<HEAD>WIVES AS THEY WERE, AND MAIDS AS THEY ARE.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT I.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I. An Apartment at Mr. Norberry's.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Sir</HI> William Dorrillon, <HI>followed by Mr.</HI> Norberry.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>WHY blame me?&mdash;Why blame me?&mdash;My &s;i&s;ter had the &s;ole management of your daughter by your own authority, from the age of &s;ix years, till within eight months of the pre&s;ent time, when, in con&s;e|quence of my &s;i&s;ter's death, &s;he was transferred to my pro|tection.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Your &s;i&s;ter, Mr. Norberry, was a prudent good woman&mdash;&s;he never could in&s;truct her in all this vice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>&mdash;Depend upon it, my dear friend, that Mi&s;s Dorrillon, your daughter, came to my hou&s;e ju&s;t the &s;ame heedle&s;s woman of fa&s;hion you now &s;ee her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm. (impatiently.</HI>)</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well&mdash;'Tis very well&mdash;But when I think on my di&s;appointment&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There is nothing which may not be repaired, Maria, with you for a guide&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Me! She turns me into ridicule&mdash;laughs at me! This morning, as &s;he was enumerating &s;ome of her frivolous expences, &s;he ob&s;erved me lift up my hands and &s;igh; on which &s;he named <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ifty other extravagances &s;he had no occa&s;ion to mention, merely to enjoy the pang which every folly of her's &s;ends to my heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But do not charge this conduct of your daugh|ter to the want of filial lov<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">&mdash;did &s;he know you were Sir
<PB N="6" REF="032304_0006_0FF1BBBFB1698940">
William Dorrillon, did &s;he know you were her father, every word you uttered, every look you glanced, would be received with gentlene&s;s and &s;ubmi&s;&s;ion:&mdash;but your pre&s;ent rebukes from Mr. Mandred (as you are called) from a perfect &s;tran|ger, as &s;he &s;uppo&s;es, &s;he con&s;iders as an impertinence which &s;he has a right to re&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h I had continued abroad. And yet, the hope of beholding her, and of be&s;towing upon her the riches I acquired, was my &s;ole &s;upport through all the toils by which I gained them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And, con&s;idering her pre&s;ent cour&s;e of life, your riches could not come more opportunely.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>She &s;hall never have a farthing of them. Do you think I have encountered the perils of almo&s;t every cli|mate, to &s;quander my hard-earned fortune upon the paltry vicious plea&s;ures in which &s;he delights? No&mdash;I have been now in your hou&s;e exactly a month&mdash;I will &s;tay but one day longer&mdash;and then, without telling her who I am, I will leave the kingdom and her for ever&mdash;Nor &s;hall &s;he know that this in&s;ignificant merchant whom &s;he de&s;pi&s;es, was her father, till he is gone, never to be recalled.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You are offended with &s;ome ju&s;tice; but, as I have often told you, your exce&s;&s;ive delicacy and re&s;pect for the conduct of the other &s;ex, degenerate into rigour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>True&mdash;for what I &s;ee &s;o near perfection as wo|man, I want to &s;ee perfect. WE, Mr. Norberry, can never be perfect; but &s;urely women, women, might ea&s;ily be made angels!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And if they were, we &s;hould &s;oon be glad to make them into women again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(inattentive to Mr. Nor.)&mdash;She</HI> &s;ets the example. <HI>She</HI> gives the fa&s;hion!&mdash;and now your whole hou&s;e, and all your vi&s;itors, in imitation of <HI>her,</HI> treat me with levity, or with contempt.&mdash;But I'll go away to-morrow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Can you de&s;ert your child in the moment &s;he mo&s;t wants your protection? That exqui&s;ite beauty ju&s;t now mature&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There's my difficulty!&mdash;There's my &s;truggle!&mdash;If &s;he were not &s;o like her mother, I could leave her with|out a pang&mdash;ca&s;t her off, and think no more of her&mdash;But that &s;hape! that face! tho&s;e &s;peaking looks! Yet, how re|ver&s;ed!&mdash;Where is the diffidence, the humility&mdash;where is the &s;implicity of my beloved wife? Bu<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ied in her grave.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="7" REF="032304_0007_0FF1BBC1413710D0">
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And, in all this great town, you may never &s;ee even its apparition.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I rejoice, however, at the &s;tratagem by which I have gained a knowledge of her heart: deprived of the means of &s;earching it in her early years, had I at pre&s;ent come as her father, &s;he might have deceived me with counterfeit man|ners, till time di&s;clo&s;ed the impo&s;ition.&mdash;Now at lea&s;t, I am not impo&s;ed upon.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Servant.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ser.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord Priory.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Lord Priory!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>An old acquaintance of mine, though we &s;el|dom meet. He has &s;ome &s;ingularities; and yet, perhaps&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lord</HI> Priory.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Lord, I am glad to &s;ee you. Mr. Mandred (<HI>introducing Sir</HI> William). My Lord, I hope I &s;ee you in perfect health.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes: but in very ill humour. I came to London early this morning with my family for the winter, and found my hou&s;e, after going through only a &s;light repair, &s;o damp, that I dare not &s;leep in it: and &s;o I am now &s;ending and going all over the town to &s;eek for lodgings.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then &s;eek no farther, but take up your lodg|ings here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To be plain with you, I called in hopes you would a&s;k me; for I am &s;o delicately &s;crupulous in re&s;pect to lady Priory that I could not bear the thought of taking her to an hotel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then pray return home, and bring her hither immediately, with all your luggage.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I am mo&s;t extremely obliged to you (<HI>very fervently</HI>); for into no one hou&s;e belonging to any of my ac|quaintance would I take my wife, &s;o &s;oon as into yours. I have now been married eleven years, and during all that time I have made it a rule never to go on a vi&s;it&punc; &s;o as to dome&s;ti|cate, in the hou&s;e of a married man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>May I enquire the rea&s;on of that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It is becau&s;e I am married my&s;elf; and ha|ving always treated my wife according to the ancient mode of treating wives, I would rather &s;he &s;hould never be an eye|witne&s;s to the modern hou&s;ehold management</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The ancients, I believe, were very affectionate <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="8" REF="032304_0008_0FF1BBC74AAC0A58">
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And they had rea&s;on to be &s;o; for their wives obeyed them. The ancients &s;eldom gave them the li|berty to do wrong: but modern wives do as they like.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And don't you &s;uffer lady Priory to do as &s;he likes?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, when it is what I like too. But never, never el&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Does not this draw on you the character of an unkind hu&s;band?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That I am proud of Did you never ob&s;erve, that &s;eldom a breach of &s;idelity in a wi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> is expo&s;ed, where the unfortunate hu&s;band is not &s;aid to be "he be&s;t creature in the world? Poor man, &s;o good-natured?&mdash;Doatingly fond of his wife!&mdash;indulged her in every thing!&mdash;How cruel in her to &s;erve him &s;o!" Now, if I am &s;erved <HI>&s;o,</HI> it &s;hall not be for my good-nature.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But I hope you equally di&s;approve of every &s;everity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory (rapidly</HI>)</SPEAKER>
<P>What do you mean by &s;everity?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You know you u&s;ed to be rather violent in your temper.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So I am &s;till&mdash;apt to be ha&s;ty and pa&s;&s;ion|ate&mdash;but that is rather of advantage to me as a hu&s;band&mdash;it cau&s;es me to be obeyed without he&s;itation&mdash;no liberty for contention, tears or repining. I in&s;ure conjugal &s;un&s;hine; by now and then introducing a &s;torm; while &s;ome hu&s;bands never &s;ee any thing but a cloudy &s;ky, and all for want of a little dome&s;tic thunder to clear away the vapours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have long conceived indulgence to be the bane of female happine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o it is.&mdash;I know &s;everal women of fa&s;hion, who will vi&s;it &s;ix places of different amu&s;ement on the &s;ame night, have company at home be&s;ides, and yet, for want of &s;omething more, they'll be out of &s;pirits; my wife never goes to a public place, has &s;carce ever company at home, and yet is always in &s;pirits.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Never vi&s;its operas, or balls, or routs?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How &s;hould &s;he? She goes to b<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">d every night exactly at ten.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>In the name of wonder, how have you been able to bring her to that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>By making her ri&s;e every morning at five.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o &s;he becomes tired before night.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="9" REF="032304_0009_0FF1BBCA571FFF88">
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Tired to death. Or, if I &s;ee her eyes completely open at bed-time, and &s;he a&s;ks me to play one game more at picquet, the next morning I jog her elbow at half after four.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But &s;uppo&s;e &s;he does not reply to the &s;ignal?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then I turn the key of the door when I leave the chamber; and there I <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ind her when I come home in the evening.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And without her having &s;een a creature all day?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That is in my favour; for not having &s;een a &s;ingle &s;oul, &s;he is rejoiced even to &s;ee <HI>me.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And will &s;he &s;peak to you after &s;uch u&s;age?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>If you only con&s;idered how much a wo|man longs to &s;peak after being kept a whole day &s;ilent, you would not a&s;k that que&s;tion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, this is the mo&s;t &s;urpri&s;ing method!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not at all. In ancient days when man|ners were &s;imple and pure, did not wives wait at the table of their hu&s;bands? and did not angels witne&s;s the &s;ubordination? I have taught Lady Priory to practi&s;e the &s;ame humble do|cile obedience&mdash;to pay re&s;pect to her hu&s;band in every &s;hape and every form&mdash;no carele&s;s inattention to <HI>me</HI>&mdash;no &s;miling politene&s;s to others in preference to <HI>me</HI>&mdash;no putting <HI>me</HI> up in a corner&mdash;in all a&s;&s;emblies, &s;he con&s;iders her hu&s;|band as the fir&s;t per&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I am impatient to &s;ee her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But don't expect a fine lady with high feathers, and the <HI>et caetera</HI> of an Ea&s;tern concubine; you will &s;ee a mode&s;t plain Engli&s;hwoman with a cap on her head&punc; a handkerchief on her neck, and a gown of her own manu|facture.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My friend Norberry, what a contra&s;t mu&s;t there be between Lady Priory and the ladies in this hou&s;e!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory (&s;tarting</HI>)</SPEAKER>
<P>Have you ladies in this hou&s;e!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Don't be alarmed; they are both &s;ingle, and can give Lady Priory no ideas concerning the marriage &s;tate.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Are you &s;ure of that? Some &s;ingle wo|men are more informed than their friends wi&s;h them to be.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>For the&s;e ladies, notwith&s;tanding a few (what <HI>you</HI> would call) exce&s;&s;es, I will an&s;wer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="10" REF="032304_0010_0FF1BBCD621C2998">
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, then, I and my wife will be with you about nine in the evening; you know we go to bed at ten.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But remember you bring your own &s;ervants to wait on you at five in the morning.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall bring but one&mdash;my old &s;ervant Oliver, who knows all my cu&s;toms &s;o well, that I never go any where without him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And is that old &s;ervant your valet &s;till?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No, he is now a kind of gentleman in wait|ing. I have had no employment for a valet &s;ince I married:&mdash;my wife, for want of di&s;&s;ipation, has not only time to attend upon her&s;elf, but upon me. Do you think I could &s;uffer a clum&s;y man to tie on my neckcloth or comb out my hair, when the &s;oft, delicate, and tender hands of my wife are at my command?</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>After this amiable de&s;cription of a woman, how can I endure to &s;ee her, whom rea&s;on bids me dete&s;t; but whom nature &s;till&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Here &s;he comes; and her companion in folly along with her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There's another woman! that Lady Mary Raffle! How can you &s;uffer &s;uch people in your hou&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>She is only on a vi&s;it for a few months&mdash;&s;he comes every winter, as her family and mine have long been intimately connected.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Let us go. I can't bear the &s;ight of them.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Going.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Stay, and for <HI>once</HI> behave with politene&s;s and good humour to your daughter&mdash;do&mdash;and I dare venture my life, &s;he will neither in&s;ult nor treat you with di&s;re&s;pect. You know you always begin fir&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Have not I a right to begin fir&s;t?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But that is a right of which &s;he is ignorant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And de&s;erves to be &s;o, and ever &s;hall be &s;o, <Q>I &s;tay and treat her with politene&s;s and good humour?</Q> No&mdash;rather let her kneel and implore my pardon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Suffer me to reveal who you are, and &s;o &s;he will.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>If you expo&s;e me only by one in&s;inuation to her knowledge, our friend&s;hip is that moment at an end.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor. (Firmly).</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have already given you my pro|mi&s;e on that &s;ubject; and you may rely upon it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I thank you&mdash;Let us go, I believe you&mdash;and I thank you.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exeunt Sir</HI> William <HI>and Mr.</HI> Norberry.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="11" REF="032304_0011_0FF1BBD0778F30B8">
<HI>Enter Lady</HI> Mary Raffle <HI>and Mi&s;s</HI> Dorrillon.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE><HI>(Stealing on as Mr.</HI> Norberry <HI>and Sir</HI> William <HI>leave the &s;tage).</HI></STAGE>
<P>They are gone. Thank heaven they are gone out of this room, for I expect a dozen vi&s;itors; and Mr. Norberry looks &s;o gloomy upon me, he puts me out of &s;pirits; while that Mr. Mandred's peevi&s;hne&s;s is not to be borne.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Be &s;atisfied; for you were tolerably &s;evere upon him this morning in your turn.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, I am vext&mdash;an<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">d I don't like to be found fault with in my be&s;t humour, much le&s;s when I have &s;o many things to tea&s;e me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What are they?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have now lo&s;t all my money, and all my jew|els at play; it is almo&s;t two years &s;ince I have received a &s;ingle remittance from my father; and Mr. Norberry refu&s;es to advance me a &s;hilling more. What I &s;hall do to di&s;charge a debt which mu&s;t be paid either to-day or to-morrow heaven knows! Dear Lady Mary, you could not lend me a &s;mall &s;um, could you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Who? I! [<HI>with &s;urpri&s;e</HI>]&mdash;My dear creature, it was the very thing I was going to a&s;k of you: for when you have money, I know no one &s;o willing to di&s;per&s;e it among her friends.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Am not I!&mdash;I prote&s;t I love to part with my money; for I know with what plea&s;ure I receive it my&s;elf, and I like to &s;ee that joy &s;parkle in another's eye, which has &s;o often brightened my own. But la&s;t night ruined me&mdash;I mu&s;t have money &s;omewhere.&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">s you can't a&s;&s;i&s;t me, I mu&s;t a&s;k Mr. Norberry for his carriage, and immediately go in &s;earch of &s;ome friend that can lend me four, or five, or &s;ix, or &s;even hundred pounds. But the wor&s;t is, I have lo&s;t my credit&mdash;Is not that dreadful?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, I know what it is.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Shaking her head.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What will become of me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why don't you marry, and throw all your misfortunes upon your hu&s;band?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why don't <HI>you</HI> marry? For you have as ma|ny to throw as I have.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But not &s;o many lovers who would be wil|ling to receive the load. I have no Sir George Evelyn with ten thou&s;and pounds a year&mdash;no Mr. Bronzely.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="12" REF="032304_0012_0FF1BBD50C594528">
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>If you have not now, you once had: for I am &s;ure Bronzely once paid his addre&s;&s;es to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And you have the vanity to &s;uppo&s;e you took him from me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Silence.&mdash;Re&s;erve your anger to de<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">end, and not to attack me. We &s;hould be allies by the common ties of poverty: and 'tis time to arm; for here's the enemy.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Sir</HI> William <HI>and Mr.</HI> Norberry.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>They are here &s;till.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>A&s;ide to Mr.</HI> Norberry, <HI>and offering to go back.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>Preventing him.</HI>) No, no.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have been waiting here, Mr. Norberry, to a&s;k a favour of you.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>He and Sir</HI> William <HI>come forward.</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>Will you be &s;o kind as to lend me your carriage for a couple of hours?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI> Mr. Mandred </SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(<HI>pointing to Sir</HI> William)</STAGE>
<P>has ju&s;t a&s;ked me for it to take him into the city.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Mr. Mandred will give it up to Mi&s;s Dorrillon, I am &s;ure; he can defer his bu&s;ine&s;s till to-morrow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No Madam&punc; &s;he may as well put off hers. I have money to receive, and I can't do it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have money to pay, and I can't do it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>If one is going to receive, and the other to pay money, I think the be&s;t way is for you to go together; and then, what deficiency there is on one &s;ide, the other may &s;upply.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Will you con&s;ent, Mr. Mandred?&mdash;Come, do; and I'll be friends with you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE><HI>(A&s;ide.</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>"She'll be friends with me!"</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Will you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well. I certainly can a&s;k a favour of Mr. Mandred better than I can of any per&s;on in the world.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why &s;o, Maria?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e, in&s;tead of pain, I can &s;ee it gives him plea&s;ure to refu&s;e me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I never confer a favour, of the mo&s;t trivial kind, where I have no e&s;teem.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Proudly)</STAGE>
<P>Nor would I receive a favour, of the mo&s;t trivial kind, from one who has not liberality to e&s;teem me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Come, Mi&s;s Dorrillon, do not grow &s;erious: laugh as much as you plea&s;e, but &s;ay nothing that&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="13" REF="032304_0013_0FF1BBD693607AD0">
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(To her impatiently.)</STAGE>
<P>From whom then can you ever receive favours, except from the vain, the idle, and the depraved?&mdash;from tho&s;e who&s;e lives are pa&s;&s;ed in begging them of others?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>They are the per&s;ons who know be&s;t how to be&s;tow them: for my part, had I not &s;ometimes felt what it was to want a friend, I might never have had humanity to be the friend of another.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Servant.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Servant.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir George Evelyn.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And pray, my dear, who&s;e friend have you ever been?&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(Enter Sir George Evelyn.)</STAGE>
<P>&mdash;Not Sir George Evelyn's, I am &s;ure; and yet he of all others de&s;erves your friend&s;hip mo&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But friend&s;hip will not content him: as &s;oon as he thought he had gained that&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He a&s;pired to the &s;upreme happine&s;s of your love.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Now you talk of "&s;upreme happine&s;s," have you provided tickets for the fete on Thur&s;day?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have; provided you have obtained Mr. Norberry's leave to go.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That I cannot grant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, my dear Sir, do not force me to go without it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(<HI>With violence.</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>Would you dare?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(<HI>Looking with &s;urpri&s;e.</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>"Would I dare," Mr. Mandred!&mdash;and what have <HI>you</HI> to &s;ay if I do?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(<HI>Recollecting him&s;elf</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>I was only going to &s;ay, that if you did, and I were Mr. Norberry&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And if you <HI>were</HI> Mr. Norberry, and treated me in the manner you now do, depend upon it <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;hould not think your approbation or di&s;approbation, your plea&s;ure or di&s;plea&s;ure, of the &s;lighte&s;t con&s;equence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>Greatly agitated.</HI>) I dare &s;ay not&mdash;I dare &s;ay not. Good morning, Sir George&mdash;I dare &s;ay not.&mdash;Good morning, Mr. Norberry.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Going.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Slopt a moment.&mdash;Maria, you have offended Mr. Mandred.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He has offended me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="14" REF="032304_0014_0FF1BBD99F2C58C0">
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(<HI>At the door, going off</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>I &s;han't offend you long.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(<HI>Going to him, and taking him by the arm</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>Stay, Mr. Mandred: Mi&s;s Dorrillon, make an apology; Mr. Mandred is my friend, and you mu&s;t not treat him with this levity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No, no apology.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No, no apology&punc; But I'll tell you what I'll do.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Goes up to Sir</HI> William.)</STAGE>
<P>&mdash;If Mr. Mandred likes, I'll &s;hake hands with him&mdash;and we'll be good friends for the future. But then, don't find fault with me&mdash;I can't bear it. <HI>You</HI> don't like to be found fault with, your&s;elf&mdash;You look as cro&s;s as any thing every time I &s;ay the lea&s;t word again&s;t you. Come, &s;hake hands; and don't let us &s;ee one another's fail|ings for the future.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There is no future for the trial.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How do you mean?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Mandred &s;ets off again for India to-mor|row.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed! I thought he was come to live in England! I am &s;orry you are going.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(<HI>With earne&s;tne&s;s</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>Why &s;orry?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e we have &s;o frequently quarrelled. I am always unhappy when I am going to be parted from a per&s;on with whom I have di&s;agreed; I often think I could part with le&s;s regret from a friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not, I &s;uppo&s;e, if the quarrel is forgiven?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! but Mr. Mandred does not forgive! no! in his looks I can always &s;ee re&s;entment&mdash;Some|times indeed I have traced a &s;park of kindne&s;s, and have gent|ly tried to blow it to a little flame of friend&s;hip; when, with one ha&s;ty puff I have put it out.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You are right. It is&mdash;I believe&mdash;extingui&s;hed.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit Mr.</HI> Norberry <HI>following.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A very &s;ingular man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! if he was not rich, there would be no bearing him&mdash;indeed he &s;eems to have lo&s;t all his friends; for during the month he has been here, I never found he had any one acquaintance out of this hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And what is very &s;trange, he has taken an aver&s;ion to me.&mdash;But it is &s;till more &s;trange, that although I
<PB N="15" REF="032304_0015_0FF1BBDB43E2E368">
know he has, yet in my heart I like <HI>him.</HI> He is moro&s;e to an in&s;ufferable degree; but then, when by chance he &s;peaks kind, you cannot imagine how it &s;oothes me.&mdash;He wants com|pa&s;&s;ion and all the tender virtues; and yet, I frequently think, that if any &s;erious misfortune were to be<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">al me, he would be the fir&s;t per&s;on to whom I &s;hould fly to complain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then why don't you <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ly and tell him of your misfortune la&s;t night.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(<HI>&s;tarting</HI>).</STAGE>
<P>What misfortune?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(<HI>to Lady Mary.</HI></STAGE>
<P>Hu&s;h!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A lo&s;s at play.&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>To Mi&s;s</HI> Dorrillon.)</STAGE>
<P>&mdash;I beg your pardon, but it was out before you &s;aid hu&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! Maria, will you &s;till ri&s;k your own and my happine&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Your happine&s;s and mine, Sir!&mdash;I beg you will not place them &s;o near to each other.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mine is &s;o firmly fixed on you, it can only exi&s;t in yours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then, when &s;he is married to Mr. Bronze|ly, you will be happy becau&s;e <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> will be &s;o?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Bronzely! has he dared?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Have not <HI>you</HI> dared, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But I believe Mr. Bronzely is the mo&s;t dar|ing of the two.&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>a&s;ide to Sir</HI> George.)</STAGE>
<P>&mdash;Take care of him.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s Dorrillon, I will not affront you by &s;up|po&s;ing that you mean &s;eriou&s;ly to receive the addre&s;&s;es of Mr. Bronzely; but I warn you again&s;t giving others, who know you le&s;s than I do, occa&s;ion to think &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I never wi&s;h to deceive any one&mdash;I do admit of Mr. Bronzely's addre&s;&s;es.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, he is the profe&s;&s;ed lover of your friend Lady Mary! or granting he denies it, and that I even pa&s;s over the frivolity of the cox<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">omo, &s;till he is unworthy of you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He &s;ays the &s;ame of you; and half a dozen more &s;ay exactly the &s;ame of each other. If you like, I'll di&s;card every one of you as unworthy; but if I retain you, I will retain the re&s;t. Which do you choo&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ubmit to any thing rather than the total lo&s;s of you&mdash;But remember, that your felicity&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>"Felicity! felicity!"&mdash;ah! that is a word
<PB N="16" REF="032304_0016_0FF1BBE0435608D0">
not to be found in the vocabulary of my &s;en&s;ations!&mdash;<HI>&s;ighing.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I believe you, and have always regarded you with a compa&s;&s;ion that has augmented my love. In your in|fancy, deprived of the watchful eye and anxious tenderne&s;s of a mother; the manly caution and authority of a father; mi&s;led by the brilliant vapour of fa&s;hion; &s;urrounded by enemies in the garb of friends&mdash;Ah! do you weep? ble&s;|&s;ed, ble&s;&s;ed be the &s;ign! Suffer me to dry tho&s;e tears I have cau&s;ed, and to give you a knowledge of true felicity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(<HI>recovering</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>I am very angry with my&s;elf.&mdash;Don't, I beg, tell Mr. Norberry or Mr. Mindred you &s;aw me cry&mdash;they'll &s;uppo&s;e I have been more indi&s;creet (<HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> her tears</HI>) than I really have. For in reality I have no|thing&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George,</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do not endeavour to conceal from me, what my tender concern for you has given me the means to become acquainted with. I know you are plunged in difficulties by your father neither &s;ending nor coming, as you once expected&mdash;I know you are &s;till deeper plunged in your fondne&s;s for play.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Very well, Sir&mdash;proceed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Thus, then&mdash;Suffer me to &s;end my &s;teward to you this morning; he &s;hall regulate your accounts, and place them in a &s;tate that &s;hall protect you from further embar|ra&s;&s;ment till your father &s;ends to you; or protect you from his reproaches, &s;hould he arrive.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sir George, I have li&s;tened to your detail of vices which I acknowledge, with patience, with humility&mdash;but your &s;u&s;picion of tho&s;e which I have <HI>not,</HI> I treat with pride, with indignation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George,</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How! &s;u&s;picion!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What part of my conduct, Sir, has made you dare to &s;uppo&s;e I would extricate my&s;elf from the difficulties that &s;urround me, by the influence I hold over the weakne&s;s of a lover?</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exeunt &s;eparately.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I. Another Apartment at Mr. Norberry's.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter two porters from an upper entrance, bringing in trunks; Lord</HI> Priory <HI>and Mr.</HI> Norberry <HI>following.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>HERE, Stephens, why are you out of the
<PB N="17" REF="032304_0017_0FF1BBE355FB1EF8">
way? Shew the men with the&s;e boxes into the dre&s;&s;ing-room appointed for my Lord Priory.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>A &s;ervant enters on the oppo&s;ite &s;ide, and the porters follow him off at a lower entrance on that &s;ide</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Sir William Dorrillon.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord, I hope I &s;ee you well this evening.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir&mdash;and you find I have literally ac|cepted Mr. Norberry's invitation, and am come to him with my luggage.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Oliver, <HI>with a &s;mall box in each hand.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory,</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Follow tho&s;e men with the tr<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">nks, Oliver.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Mr. Oliver, how do you do?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oliver,</SPEAKER>
<P>Pretty well&mdash;tolerably well! I thank you, Sir.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Ex.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Servant.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Priory.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lady</HI> Priory.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory (to her</HI>)</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Norberry, our worthy ho&s;t; and Mr. Mandred</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>She curi&s;ies.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I hope your lady&s;hip will find my hou&s;e &s;o little inconvenient to you, as to induce you to make no very &s;hort vi&s;it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have no doubt, Sir, but I &s;hall find, from your friend&s;hip, every comfort in this hou&s;e which it is po&s;&s;ible for me to enjoy out of my own.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lady Mary</HI> Raffle <HI>and Mi&s;s</HI> Dorrillon.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(<HI>introducing them.</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>Lady Priory&mdash;Lady Mary Raffle&mdash;Mi&s;s Dorrillon&mdash;Lord Priory.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Permit me, Lady Priory, to take you to the next room: we are going to have tea immediately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have drank tea, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Already! It is only nine o'clock.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then it is near my hour of going to bed.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Lord</HI> Priory, <HI>Sir</HI> William, <HI>and Mr.</HI> Norberry, <HI>retire to the back of the &s;tage, and talk apart.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Go to bed already! in the name of won|der, what time did you ri&s;e this morning?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, I do think it was almo&s;t &s;ix o'clock.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE><HI>(in amaze.</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>And were you up at &s;ix this morning?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory,</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>At &s;ix in the month of January!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It is not light till eight: and what good, now could you po&s;&s;ibly be doing for two hours by candle-light?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="18" REF="032304_0018_0FF1BBB0626D1C40">
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, Lady Mary, at what time did you go to bed?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>About three this morning.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And what good could you po&s;&s;ibly be do|ing for eleven hours by candle-light?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Good! It's as much as can be expected from a woman of fa&s;hion&punc; if &s;he does no harm.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But I &s;hould fear you would do a great deal of harm to your health, your &s;pirits, and the tranquillity of your mind.</P>
<STAGE>[<HI>Mr.</HI> Norberry <HI>goes off&mdash;Lord</HI> Priory <HI>and Sir</HI> William <HI>come forward.</HI>]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, my Lord Priory, I realy find all the accounts I have heard of your education for a wife to be actu|ally true!&mdash;and I can't help laughing to think, if you and I chanced to have married together, what a different creature you mo&s;t likely would have made of me, to what I am at pre&s;ent!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; and what a different creature you mo&s;t likely would have made of <HI>me,</HI> to what I am at pre&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Lady <HI>Priory</HI> I am not accu&s;tomed to pay com|pliments, or to &s;peak my approbation, even when prai&s;e is a ju&s;t tribute; but your virtues compel me to an eulogium.&mdash;That wi&s;e &s;ubmi&s;&s;ion to a hu&s;band who loves you, that cheerful &s;mile &s;o expre&s;&s;ive of content, and that plain dre&s;s which indicates the elegance as well as the &s;implicity, of your mind, are all &s;ymbols of a heart &s;o unlike to tho&s;e which the pre&s;ent fa&s;hion of the day has mi&s;led&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why look &s;o &s;tedfa&s;tly on me, Mr. Man|dred? Do you pretend to &s;ee my heart?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Have you any?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; and one large enough to hold&mdash;even my enemy.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Servant.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Servant.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Bronzely.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Shew him into the other room.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit Ser|vant.]</STAGE>
<P>Come, Lady Priory we mu&s;t introduce you to Mr. Bronzely: he is one of the mo&s;t fa&s;hionable, agreeable, plea|&s;ant, whim&s;ical unthinking, and &s;pirited creatures in all the world: you'll be charmed&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I dare <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> it's near ten o'clock. I am afraid I &s;han't be able to keep awake.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You mu&s;t&mdash;We are going to have a little con|cert&mdash;'Twill be impo&s;&s;ible to &s;leep.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="19" REF="032304_0019_0FF1BBEAE6F0DF40">
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my word, my Lord, your plan of management has made your wife unfit for company.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So much more fit to be a wife.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>She is ab&s;olutely fatigued with hard labour&mdash;for &s;hame!&mdash;How does hou&s;ehold drudgery become her hand?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Much better than cards and dice do yours.</P>
<STAGE>[<HI>Exit Lady Mary followed by Lord</HI> Prior,&mdash;<HI>Sir</HI> William <HI>is left on the &s;tage alone.</HI>]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>She "has a heart large enough to receive her enemy."&mdash;And by that enemy &s;he menas her father.</P>
<STAGE>[<HI>He &s;its down, and &s;hew<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> marks of inquietude. Enter Sir</HI> George Evelyn.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I beg your pardon, Mr. Mandred&mdash;I hope I don't interrupt you&mdash;I only wi&s;hed to &s;peak to Mi&s;s Dor|rillon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>She is ju&s;t gone into the next room,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To the concert?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Are not you invited?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; but before I go in, I wi&s;h to know who are the company.&mdash;Can you tell whether&mdash;a Mr. Bron|zely is there?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I know he is.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Are you acquainted with him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have met him here frequently.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And are you <HI>certain</HI> he is here at pre&s;ent?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have rea&s;on to be certain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Any particular rea&s;on?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Your mi&s;tre&s;s, when his name was announced, went out to him, exclaiming "he was the mo&s;t charming and accompli&s;hed man in the world."</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(<HI>greatly agitated.</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>She loves him, Sir&mdash;I have rea&s;on to believe&mdash;to know &s;he loves him. Thus &s;he gives up my happine&s;s and her own, to gratify the vanity of a man who has no real regard for her; but who&s;e predominant pa&s;|&s;ion is to enjoy the villanous name of a general &s;educer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(<HI>ri&s;ing.</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>Why do you &s;uffer it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hu<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">h! Don't repeat what I have &s;aid, or I lo&s;e her for ever. I am at pre&s;ent under her re&s;entment; and have ju&s;t &s;ent into the next room, to a&s;k, if &s;he were there, to &s;peak with her.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mi&s;s</HI> Dorrillon.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dorrillon.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And is it po&s;&s;ible I was &s;ent for by you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Don't be offended, that I &s;hould be unea&s;y and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="20" REF="032304_0020_0FF1BBEDEE2AD900">
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I can't forgive you, Sir, 'ti<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> impo&s;&s;ible.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Going.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You pardon tho&s;e, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> a, who offend you more.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But an ungrateful mind always prefers the un|worthy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Mr. Mandred, are you there? (<HI>playfully</HI> And have you undertaken to be &s;ir George's coun&s;el? If you have, I believe he mu&s;t lo&s;e his cau&s;e. To fit you for the tender ta&s;k of advocate in love,&mdash;have you ever been admitted an honourable member of that court? Have you, with all that &s;olemn wi&s;dom of which you are ma&s;ter, &s;tudied Ovid, as our great laywers &s;tudy Black&s;tone? If you have&mdash;&s;hew cau&s;e&mdash;why plaintiff has a right to defendant's heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A man of fortune, of family, and of character, ought at lea&s;t to be treated with re&s;pect, and with honour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You mean to &s;ay, <Q>That <HI>A</HI> is beloved by <HI>B,</HI> why &s;hould not <HI>A</HI> be con&s;trained to return <HI>B</HI>'s love?</Q> Coun&s;ellor for defendant&mdash;<Q>Becau&s;e, moreover, and be&s;ides <HI>B</HI> who has a claim on defendant's heart, there are al&s;o <HI>C, D, E, F,</HI> and <HI>G;</HI> all of whom put in their &s;eparate claims&mdash;and what, in this ca&s;e, can poor <HI>A</HI> do? She is willing to part and divide her love, &s;hare and &s;hare alike; But <HI>B</HI> will have all or none: &s;o poor <HI>A</HI> mu&s;t remain <HI>A</HI> by her&s;elf <HI>A</HI></Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do you think I would accept of a &s;hare of your heart!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do you think I could afford to give it you all? "Be&s;ides," &s;ays defendant's coun&s;ellor, <Q>I will prove that plaintiff <HI>B</HI> has no heart to give defendant in return&mdash;he has, indeed, a pul&s;ation on the left &s;ide; but as it never beat with any thing but &s;u&s;picion and jealou&s;y; in the laws of love, it is not termed, admitted, or con&s;idered a <HI>heart.</HI></Q></P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Going.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Geoege.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Where are you going?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To the mu&s;ic-room, to be &s;ure: and if you fol|low me, it &s;hall be to &s;ee me treat every per&s;on there better than your&s;elf&mdash;and Mr. Bronzely, whom you hate to &s;ee me treat him be&s;t of all.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mu&s;t follow you, though to death.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Wm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fool,&mdash;and yet am not I near<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">y as weak as he is? El&s;e why do <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">inger in this hou&s;e? Why feed my hopes with &s;ome propitious moment to waken her to repentance? Why <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> anxiou&s;ly wi&s;h to ward off &s;ome dreadful fate?&mdash;If &s;he would marry &s;ir George, now&mdash;if &s;he would give me
<PB N="21" REF="032304_0021_0FF1BBEF75AC66F8">
only <HI>one</HI> proof of di&s;cretion, I think I would endeavour to take her to my heart.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mr.</HI> Bronzely, <HI>in great ha&s;te.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear &s;ir, will you do me the greate&s;t favour in the world?&mdash;You mu&s;t do it in an in&s;tant too. Do, my dear &s;ir, a&s;k no que&s;tions; but lend me your coat for a &s;ingle moment, and take mine&mdash;only for a moment&mdash;I cannot explain rea&s;ons now, my impatience is &s;o great;&mdash;but, the in&s;tant you have complied, I will inform you of the whole &s;ecret; and you will for ever rejoice that you granted my reque&s;t.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Pulling off his coat.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>a&s;ide, with great &s;corn.</HI>) And this very con|temptible fellow is the favoured lover of my daughter!&mdash;I'll&mdash;<HI>(after a &s;truggle)</HI>&mdash;yes&mdash;I'll make my&s;elf ma&s;ter of his &s;ecret&mdash;it may po&s;&s;ibly concern her&mdash;my child&mdash;my child's &s;afety may depend upon it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Mr. Mandred, no time is to be lo&s;t!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>This is rather a &s;trange reque&s;t, Mr. Bron|zely. However, your fervency convinces me you mu&s;t have &s;ome very forcible rea&s;on.&mdash;There's my coat, Sir.</P>
<STAGE>(Gives it him.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank you, dear Sir, a thou&s;and times.&mdash;This goodne&s;s I &s;hall forever remember&mdash;This binds me to you forever!&mdash;<HI>(putting it on.)</HI> Thank you, Sir, a thou&s;and times!</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Bowing, dre&s;&s;ed, and compo&s;ed.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(after putting on the other coat.)</HI> And now, Sir, explain the cau&s;e of this metamorpho&s;is&mdash;let me have the &s;atisfaction to know what advantage will accrue from it; and in what I have to rejoice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will you promi&s;e me not to reveal the &s;ecret, if I tru&s;t you with it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Would you add conditions after the bargain is made? I mu&s;t know your &s;ecret in&s;tantly.</P>
<STAGE>(Threatening.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I will di&s;clo&s;e it to you voluntarily; and rely on your honour to keep it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(attentively.)</HI> Well, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hark! I thought I heard &s;omebody coming!</P>
<STAGE><HI>(<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> to go.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I in&s;i&s;t upon the information.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Laying hold of him.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, then, Sir&mdash;well&mdash;you &s;hall&mdash;you &s;hall.&mdash;Then, Sir&mdash;in the &s;mall gallery, which &s;eparates the mu&s;ic-room from the re&s;t of the&s;e apartments&mdash;in that little
<PB N="22" REF="032304_0022_0FF1BBF0FB3BA688">
gallery, the lamp, unfortunately, is ju&s;t gone out.&mdash;I was (as unfortunately) coming along, when the whi&s;king of a woman's gown made me give a &s;udden &s;tart!&mdash;I found a per&s;on was in the gallery with me, and in the dark.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well&punc; Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o, confidently a&s;&s;uring my&s;elf, that it was Mi&s;s Dorrillon's waiting-maid, or Lady Mary's waiting-maid, I mo&s;t unluckily cla&s;ped my arms around her, and took one ki&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Only one?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>There might be half a dozen! I won't pre|tend to &s;wear to one. We'll &s;ay half a dozen, before I knew who &s;he was. My rapidity would not let her breathe at fir&s;t, and &s;he was fairly &s;peechle&s;s. But the moment &s;he recovered her breath, &s;he cry'd, "Villain! whoever you are, you will repent this;"&mdash;and I found it was the voice of a lady to whom I had ju&s;t been introduced in the concert-room, one Lady Pri|ory&mdash;It &s;eems &s;he was &s;tealing to bed at the time we unhap|pily met.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But what has this to do with your coat?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>A great deal, &s;ir&mdash;you will find a great deal.&mdash;As I perceived &s;he did not know me, I carefully held my tongue&mdash;but &s;he, with her prudi&s;h notions, called "Help!" and "Murder!" On which, I flew to the door, to get away before the lights could be brought&mdash;&s;he flew after me; and, as I went out, exclaimed&mdash;<Q>Don't hope to conceal your&s;elf: I &s;hall know you among the whole concert-room; for I carry &s;ci&s;&s;ors hanging at my &s;ide, and I have cut a piece off your coat.</Q>&mdash;[<HI>Sir</HI> William <HI>looks ha&s;tily at his coat&mdash;on which</HI> Bron|zely <HI>holds up the part cut&punc;</HI>]&mdash;and &s;ure enough, &s;o &s;he had!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>in anger.</HI>) And what, &s;ir, am I to have the di&s;grace&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Either you or I mu&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Wm.</SPEAKER>
<P>And do you dare&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Con&s;ider, my dear &s;ir, how much le&s;s the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ault is, if perpetrated by you, than by me! This is the fir&s;t of|fence of the kind which, I dare &s;ay, you have committed this many a year; and it will be overlooked in <HI>you.</HI> But I have been &s;u&s;pected of two or three things of the &s;ame &s;ort within a very &s;hort time; and I &s;hould never be forgiven.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Wm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nor ought you to be forgiven&mdash;it would be &s;candalous in me to connive&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>But would it not be more &s;candalous to reveal
<PB N="23" REF="032304_0023_0FF1BBF289F25F18">
the &s;ecret of a per&s;on who confided in you?&mdash;who flew to you in di&s;tre&s;s, as his friend, the partner of his cares?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Wm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your impertinence to me, but more your of|fence to a woman of virtue, de&s;erves puni&s;hment. Yet I think the puni&s;hment of death, in the way that a man of my Lord Priory's temper might inflict it, much too honourable for your de&s;erts; &s;o I &s;ave your life for &s;ome le&s;s creditable end. I lend you my coat, to di&s;grace you by exi&s;tence; and will go to my chamber, and put on another m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;elf. (<HI>Pa&s;&s;es</HI> Bronzel, <HI>in order to retire to his chamber.</HI>)</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lord</HI> Priory, <HI>who meets him. Sir</HI> Wm. <HI>&s;tarts.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>[<HI>going up to Lord</HI> Priory.) Ah, my Lord! is the concert over? charming mu&s;ic! that <HI>&s;olo</HI> was divine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>[<HI>Sir</HI> Wm.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>&s;teals to a chair, and &s;its down to hide his coat.</HI>]</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Lord</HI> Priory</SPEAKER>
<P>[<HI>after looking inqui&s;itively at</HI> Bronzely's <HI>dre&s;s.]</HI> It is time the concert &s;hould be over&mdash;it had been better it had never begun; for there have been &s;ome very improper per&s;ons admitted. [<HI>In great anger.</HI>]</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>[<HI>affecting &s;urpri&s;e.</HI>] Indeed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Lord</HI> Priory</SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>trembling with rage</HI>) I am at a lo&s;s how to act. (<HI>Draws a chair with violence, and places him&s;elf down by Sir</HI> William&mdash;<HI>Sir</HI> William <HI>appears di&s;concerted and unea&s;y.</HI>) But if I could find the man to whom this piece of cloth belongs&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! this &s;mall piece of woolen cloth?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, then I &s;hould know how to act. In the mean time, Mr Mandred, as I know you are a great ad|mirer of my wife [<HI>Sir</HI> William <HI>&s;tarts</HI>], and a grave prudent man of honour, I come to a&s;k your advice, how I am the mo&s;t likely to find out the villain who has dared to in&s;ult her; for a gro&s;s in&s;ult &s;he has received from one of Mr. Norberry's vi|&s;itors, wearing a coat of which this is a part.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>The villain, no doubt, &s;tole out of the hou&s;e immediately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I ordered the &s;treet door to be guarded that in&s;tant&mdash;and you, Mr. Bronzely, are now the la&s;t man who&s;e habit I have examined.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>And you &s;ee I am perfectly whole. [<HI>turning round.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I do &s;ee&mdash;I do &s;ee. [<HI>Sir</HI> William <HI>moves about on his chair, and appears greatly embarra&s;&s;ed. Lord</HI> Pri|ory <HI>&s;tarts up in a violent pa&s;&s;ion&mdash;Sir</HI> William <HI>&s;tarts up with him.</HI>]</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="24" REF="032304_0024_0FF1BBF4D5DD7D08">
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I'll find him out if he is on earth&mdash;I'll find him out if&mdash;My pa&s;&s;ion carries me away&mdash;I have not coolne&s;s to detect him my&s;elf&mdash;I'll employ another&mdash;I'll &s;end Oliver in &s;earch. Oliver! [<HI>calling</HI>] Oliver! here, Oli|ver! Why don't you an&s;wer when you are called, you &s;tupid, dull, idle, forgetful, blundering, carele&s;s, &s;elf-&s;ufficient&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>[Exit in a fury.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Wm.</SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>ri&s;ing with great dignity.</HI>) And now, Mr. Bronzely, how do you think you are to repay me, for having fe<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">t one tran&s;itory moment of &s;hame? Under&s;tand, Sir, that &s;hame is one of the misfortunes to which I have never&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lady</HI> Mary.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely</SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>A&s;ide to Sir</HI> Wm) Sit down, &s;it down&mdash;&s;it down&mdash;hold your tongue, and &s;it down.</P>
<STAGE>[<HI>Sir</HI> William <HI>reluctantly retires to his chair.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Lady</HI> Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I do mo&s;t cordially rejoice, when peevi&s;h, &s;u&s;picious, and cen&s;orious people, meet with humi|liation! I could die with laughing at the incident which has put both my Lord and my Lady Priory into the greate&s;t ter|ror, grief, and rage.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Wm.</SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>ri&s;ing.</HI>) I am out of all patience. The malicious depravity of per&s;ons in a certain &s;phere of life is not to be borne. [<HI>With firmne&s;s and &s;olemnity.</HI>] Lady Mary&mdash;Mr. Bronzely&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely</SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>in a half whi&s;per to him.</HI>) Go away&mdash;don't expo&s;e your&s;elf&mdash;&s;teal out of the room&mdash;take my advice, and go to bed&mdash;hide your&s;elf. So great is my re&s;pect for you, I would not have you detected for the world.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Wm.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am going to retire, &s;ir. I would not throw my friend's hou&s;e into confu&s;ion and broils; therefore I am as well plea&s;ed not to be detected as you can be. (<HI>Goes to the door, then turns.</HI>) But before I quit the room, I am irre&s;i&s;ti|bly impelled to &s;ay&mdash;Mr. Bronzely! Lady Mary! while you continue to ridicule all that is virtuous, e&s;timable, digni|fied, your vices mo&s;t a&s;&s;uredly will plunge you into that very di&s;grace&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(<HI>Enter</HI> Oliver, <HI>and places the piece of cloth again&s;t Sir</HI> Wil|liam's <HI>coat.</HI>)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oliver.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis as exact a match as ever was&mdash;it fits to a thread. Ha, ha, ha!&mdash;Ha, ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Wm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ra&s;cal!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did not I entreat you to go to-bed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="25" REF="032304_0025_0FF1BBFC6C5C2F98">
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! this is the highe&s;t gratification I ever knew. My Lord! my Lord! (<HI>calling.</HI>)</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h, hu&s;h!&mdash;hold, for heaven's &s;ake.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oliver.</SPEAKER>
<P>But mercy and goodne&s;s defend us! who would have thought of this grave gentleman? Ha, ha, ha!&mdash;I can tell you what, &s;ir; my Lord will be in a terrible pa&s;&s;ion with you. This hou&s;e won't ho<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">d you both; and I am &s;ure I hate to make mi&s;chief.&mdash;Mum&mdash;I'll &s;ay nothing about it. (<HI>clapping Sir</HI> William <HI>on the &s;houlder.</HI>) And &s;o make your|&s;elf ea&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely</SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>on the other &s;ide of Sir</HI> William.) Yes, make your&s;elf ea&s;y.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oliver&punc;</SPEAKER>
<P>A good &s;ervant &s;hould &s;ometimes be a peace|maker&mdash;for my part, I have faults of my own, and &s;o, I dare &s;ay, has that gentleman&mdash;and &s;o, I dare &s;ay, has that gentlewoman. But of all the birds in the wood, how came you to make up to my Lady? Ha, ha, ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>No je&s;ts&mdash;no je&s;ts. Mr. Mandred is my be&s;t friend.&mdash;and he is not &s;o much to b<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ame as you think, for&mdash;Good night, my dear &s;ir. Heaven ble&s;s you. I thank you a thou&s;and times. Good night. <HI>(Shaking hands with Sir</HI> William, <HI>and leading him towards the door)</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(with &s;teady compo&s;ure)</HI> Good night. Good night. Lady Mary.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oliver.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, he never &s;o much as once &s;aid he was o|bliged to me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I am &s;ure, if you do not di&s;cover this to your ma&s;ter, I will.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oliver.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! as that old gentleman had not manners to &s;ay "thank you for your kindne&s;s," I'll go tell my Lord di|rectly.</P>
<STAGE>(Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(running after him.)</HI> No, no, no&mdash;&s;top Oliver. He is gone!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What makes you thus anxious and concer|ned, Bronzely? Now, I wi&s;h I may &s;uffer death, if, ti<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">l I came into this room, I did not think <HI>you</HI> were the offender.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 words"> indeed!&mdash;No, if I could have been tempted to offend any woman in this hou&s;e in a &s;imilar man|ner, it could have been none but you.</P>
<STAGE>[Bowing</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No, Bronzely, no; I have been too par|tial
<PB N="26" REF="032304_0026_0FF1BBFDF3C36B48">
to you, to have any remaining claims&mdash;Hark! don't I hear Lord Priory's voice in a dreadful rage?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then Oliver has accu&s;ed him&punc; What &s;hall I do to prevent mi&s;chief? Dear Lady Mary, as it is not pro|per for me to &s;tay here any <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">onger uninvited, do you run and try to pacify my Lord Priory. Te<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> him Mandred does not &s;leep here to-night; and in the morning you are &s;ure he will make an apology.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I will do as you de&s;ire&mdash;but I know Mr. Mandred &s;o well, that I am &s;ure he will <HI>not.</HI></P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I will for him. Early in the morning, I'll wait on Lady Priory, and beg pardon in his name without his knowing it. Yes, I have got poor Mandred into a dif|ficulty, and it is my duty to get him out of it. And then, I &s;hall not only &s;erve him, but have one interview more with that heavenly woman.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
