<P>[<HI>Drawing Sir</HI> William <HI>on one &s;ide.</HI>] I will&mdash;I will &s;et every thing to rights. It would be ba&s;e in me if I did not; and I will. (<HI>Turns to Lord</HI> Priory <HI>and Lady</HI> Mary.) Yes, Mr&punc; Mandred, I will retrieve <HI>your</HI> character at the ex|pence of my <HI>own.</HI> I am more able to contend with the frenzy of a jealous hu&s;band than you are&mdash;(<HI>Enter Mi&s;s</HI> Dorril on <HI>and Sir</HI> George Evelyn.)&mdash;I am happy to &s;ee <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&mdash;you are ju&s;t come in time to hear me clear the grave, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">pectable character of my friend Mr. Mandred, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">i&s;e my own.&mdash;My Lord, vent all your anger an<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> upon me. It was I [pray believe me, I beg you will; <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">n't doubt my word], it was I who committed the offence of which my friend, the man I re&s;pect and reverence, &s;tands accu&s;ed&mdash;It was I who offended my Lady Priory, and then&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
