<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(to Sir</HI> William) Now how can you be &s;o provoking?&mdash;Nay, hold Sir George, <HI>(he offers to go)</HI> you &s;hall not go away with that frowning brow. <HI>(She draws him gently towards Sir</HI> William, <HI>then takes Sir</HI> William's <HI>hand)</HI> Nor you, with yours&mdash;Come &s;hake hands for my &s;ak<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">.&mdash;Now, as I live, Sir George, Mr. Mandred's hand fee<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">s war|mer and kinder than yours&mdash;he tries to draw it back, but he has not the heart. (<HI>Sir</HI> William <HI>&s;natches it away as by compul|&s;ion.</HI>)&mdash;Thou art a &s;trange per&s;onage!&mdash;thou wilt not &s;uffer me either to prai&s;e or to di&s;prai&s;e thee&mdash;Come Sir George, make up this difference&mdash;for if you were to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ight, and Mr. Mandred was to fall&mdash;</P>
