<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He &s;aid &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o it was&mdash;it was of importance <HI>then</HI>&mdash;ju&s;t at the very time I was &s;peaking to Lady Priory on the &s;ubject.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;aid &s;o but this very moment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Come, come, tell it immediately, what|ever it is. Come, let us hear it.&mdash;(<HI>after waiting &s;ome time</HI>) Why, Sir, you look as if you were a&s;hamed of it? What can be the meaning of this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be plain, my lord, my &s;ecret will di&s;clo&s;e the folly of a per&s;on for whom I have a &s;incere regard.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No matter&mdash;let every fool look like a fool, and every villain be known for what he is&mdash;Tell your &s;tory.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How can you deprive me of the plea&s;ure you promi&s;ed? You &s;aid it would prevent every future care.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Explain, Sir. I begin to feel my&s;elf not quite &s;o compo&s;ed as I expected. You never, perhaps, &s;aw <HI>me</HI> in a pa&s;&s;ion&mdash;&s;he has&mdash;and if you were once to &s;ee me really angry&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely,</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, my lord, I am apt to be pa&s;&s;ionate too&mdash;and I boldly tell you, that what I had to reveal, tho' per|fectly proper, was meant for lady Priory alone to hear. I en|treated your lady&s;hip not to mention to my lord that I had any thing to communicate, and you gave me a &s;olemn promi&s;e you would <HI>not.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my honour, during our whole con|ver&s;ation upon that &s;ubject, you never named my lord Priory's name.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>I charged you to keep what I had to tell you a profound &s;ecret.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; but I thought you under&s;tood I could have no &s;ecrets from my hu&s;band.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>You promi&s;ed no one &s;hould know it but your&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He is <HI>my&s;elf.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory. </HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How, Mr. Bronzely, did you &s;uppo&s;e &s;he and I were two? Perhaps you did, and that we wanted a third. Well, I quite forgive you for your &s;i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ly mi&s;take, and laugh at you, ha, ha, ha, as I did at Mr. Mandred (<HI>&s;eri|ou&s;ly</HI>&mdash;Did you &s;uppo&s;e, &s;ir, we lived like per&s;ons of fa&s;hion of the modern <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">? Did you imagine that a woman of her
<PB N="38" REF="032304_0038_0FF1BC22DD41D670">
character could have a wi&s;h, a de&s;ire, even a thought, a &s;e|cret from her hu&s;band?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is amazing to find &s;o much fidelity the re|ward of tyranny!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sir&mdash;I &s;peak with humility&mdash;I would not wi&s;h to give offence&mdash;(<HI>timidly</HI>)&mdash;But to the be&s;t of my ob&s;er|vation and under&s;tanding, your &s;ex, in re&s;pect to us, are <HI>all tyrants.</HI> I was born to be the &s;lave of &s;ome of you&mdash;I make the choice to obey my hu&s;band.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Mr. Bronzely; and I believe it is more her happine&s;s to be my &s;lave, than your friend&mdash;to live in fear of me, than in love with you&mdash;Lady Priory, leave the room.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit Lady</HI> Priory.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do you &s;ee&mdash;did you ob&s;erve the glow of truth and candour which te&s;tifies that woman's faith? and do you not blu&s;h at having attempted it? Call me a tyrant! Where are the &s;igns? Oh, if every married man would follow my &s;y&s;tem in the management of his wife, every impertinent lo|ver would look ju&s;t as fooli&s;h as you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is all boa&s;ting, my lord&mdash;you live in con|tinual fear&mdash;for (without meaning any offence to lady Priory's honour) you know you dare not tru&s;t her one hour alone with any man under &s;ixty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I dare tru&s;t her at any time with a coxcomb.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely&punc;</SPEAKER>
<P>That is declaring I am not one&mdash;for I am cer|tain you dare not tru&s;t her alone with me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>in a pa&s;&s;ion</HI>) Yes, with fifty &s;uch.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>But not with one&mdash;and you are right, it might be dangerous.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(angrily)</HI> No, it would not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(&s;ignificantly)</HI> Yes, it would.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Have not you had a trial?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>But you were pre&s;ent. You con&s;tantly follow all her &s;teps, watch all &s;he &s;ays and does. But I believe you are right&mdash;wives are not to be tru&s;ted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mine is.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, my dear lord Priory, you mu&s;t fir&s;t be|come gentle, before you can po&s;itively con<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ide in her affection&mdash;before you can tru&s;t her in a hou&s;e, or in any place, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> one.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(ha&s;tily)</HI> To prove you are mi&s;taken, I'll in|&s;tantly go back to my friend Norberry's, and leave you here to tell her the &s;ecret you boa&s;ted. Pay your addre&s;&s;es to her, if that is the &s;ecret&mdash;you have my free con<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="39" REF="032304_0039_0FF1BC2613EB3E40">
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear friend, I'll accept it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, I &s;ee you have hopes of &s;upplanting me, by calling me your friend&mdash;But can you conceive now that &s;he'll li&s;ten to you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have given me leave to try, and can't recal it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But depend upon it, you will meet with &s;ome terrible humiliation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Either you or I &s;hall.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall laugh to hear you tumbled down &s;tairs.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are not to remain on the watch here; you are to return to Mr. Norberry's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Was that the bargain?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't you remember? You &s;aid &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, if that will give you any &s;atisfaction&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>It will give me great &s;atisfaction.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven forgive me, but your confidence makes me laugh. Ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>And your's makes me laugh.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Oliver.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hah! What brings you here, Oliver? Lady Priory and I are only come home for a few hours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oliver.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know it, my Lord. I thought neverthele&s;s I might be wanted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o you are, good Mr. Oliver. Your Lord de&s;ires you to conduct me to your Lady in the next room, and acquaint her it is with his permi&s;&s;ion I am come to conclude the conver&s;ation which was ju&s;t now interrupted&mdash;Is not that right, my Lord? Are not tho&s;e words exactly corre&s;pond|ing with your kind promi&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I believe they are.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oliver.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am "to take Mr. Bronzely to my Lady, and tell her you &s;ent him"</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit</HI> Oliver.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now this is perfect fa&s;hion; and while I &s;tep to Lady Priory, do you go and comfort my intended wife, Lady Mary.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I hate the fa&s;hion&mdash;and were I not &s;ure you would now be received in a very unfa&s;hionable manner&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>No rough dealings, I hope?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, you begin to be afraid, do you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;but I have met with an accident or two lately&mdash;and I am not &s;o well acquainted with ancient u&s;ages as to know in what manner a man of my pur&s;uits would have been treated in former times.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="40" REF="032304_0040_0FF1BC281EAE4750">
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A man of your pur&s;uits. Mr. Bronzely, is of a very late date; and to be &s;hamed out of them by a wife like mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then we &s;hall all three be old-fa&s;hioned.</P>
<STAGE><HI>(Exit, following</HI> Oliver.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(returning and looking anxiou&s;ly after</HI> Bron.) I am pa&s;&s;ionate&mdash;I am precipitate&mdash;I have no command over my temper.&mdash;However, if a man cannot govern him&s;elf, yet he will never make any very de&s;picable figure, as long as he knows how to govern his wife.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE III. Sir Wm.'s Apartment at Mr. Norberry's.&mdash;Se|veral trunks and travelling-boxes.&mdash;Sir Wm. di&s;covered, packing writings into a port-folio.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And here is the end of my voyage to England!&mdash;a voyage, which for years, my mind has dwelt on with delight!&mdash;I pictured to my&s;elf my daughter grown to wo|manhood, beautiful! and &s;o &s;he is.&mdash;Accompli&s;hed! and &s;o &s;he is.&mdash;Virtuous! and &s;o &s;he is.&mdash;Am I of a di&s;contented nature then, that I am not &s;atisfied?&mdash;Am I too nice?&mdash;Per|haps I am.&mdash;Soothing thought!&mdash;I will for a moment cheri&s;h it, and dwell with &s;ome little gratitude upon her late anxiety for my &s;afety. [<HI>He walks about in a thoughtful mu&s;ing manner.</HI></P>
<P><HI>A loud thru&s;ting and rapping is heard at his chamber door.</HI></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Mi&s;s <HI>Dor. ha&s;tily and in affright.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Mr. Mandred, I beg your pardon&mdash;I did not know this was your apartment. But &s;uffer me to lock the door: [<HI>&s;he locks it</HI>] and conceal me for a moment, for heaven's &s;ake.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What's the matter? Why have you locked my door?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>[<HI>trembling</HI>]. I dare not tell you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I in&s;i&s;t upon knowing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why then&mdash;I am pur&s;ued by a&mdash;I cannot name the horrid name&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nab&s;on</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(without.)</HI> She went into this room.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>to Sir</HI> Wm.) Go to the door, and &s;ay I did not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nab&s;on</SPEAKER>
<P>[<HI>without.</HI>] Plea&s;e to open the door.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Threaten to beat him if he won't go away.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Give me the key, and let me &s;ee from whom you want to hide.&mdash;[<HI>commandingly</HI>]&mdash;Give me the key.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>[<HI>collecting firmne&s;s.</HI>] I will not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>[<HI>&s;tarting.</HI>] "Will not"&mdash;"Will not", when I de&s;ire you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="41" REF="032304_0041_0FF1BC2B689075E0">
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;&s;ince you refu&s;e me protection, I'll pro|tect my&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But you had better not have made u&s;e of that expre&s;&s;ion to me&mdash;you had better not. Reca<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">l it by giving me the key.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>If I do, will you let me conceal my&s;elf behind that book-ca&s;e, and &s;ay I am not here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Utter a fal&s;ehood?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I would for you. [<HI>A hammering at the door.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>They are breaking open the door.&mdash;Give me the key, I command you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>"Command me!" "command me!" How|ever there it is. [<HI>Gives it him.</HI>] And now, if you are a gen|tleman, give me up if you dare!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>"If I am a gentleman!" Hem, hem&mdash;"If I am a gentleman!" "Dares" me too!</P>
<STAGE>[Going &s;lowly towards the door.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes. I have now thrown my&s;elf upon your protection: and if you deliver me to my enemies&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What enemies? What bu&s;ine&s;s have you with enemies?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis they have bu&s;ine&s;s with me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>[<HI>to them without.</HI>] I am coming. The door &s;hall be opened.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>[<HI>follows and lays hold of him.</HI>] Oh, for heaven's &s;ake, have pity on me&mdash;they are mercile&s;s creditors&mdash;I &s;hall be d<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">gged to a pri&s;on. Do not deliver me up&mdash;I am unfortunate&mdash;I am overwhelmed with misfortune&mdash;have compa&s;&s;ion on me! <HI>(She falls on her knees.)</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>in great agitation</HI>) Don't <HI>kneel</HI> to me!&mdash;I don't mean you to kneel to me!&mdash;What makes you think of kneeling to <HI>me?</HI>&mdash;I mu&s;t do my duty. (<HI>He unlocks the door.</HI></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Nab&s;on&mdash;<HI>Mi&s;s</HI> Dorrillon <HI>&s;teals behind the book-ca&s;e.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What did you want, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nab&s;on.</SPEAKER>
<P>lady, that I have ju&s;t this minute made my pri&s;oner; but &s;he ran from me, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ocked her&s;elf in here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>[<HI>with &s;urpri&s;e.</HI>] A<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">e&s;ted a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ady!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nab&s;on.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir; and if <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ou mean to deny her being here, I mu&s;t make bold to &s;earch the room.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Let me look at your credent<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">s&mdash;(<HI>takes the writ</HI>)&mdash;"Elizabeth Dorrillon for &s;ix hundred pounds." Pray &s;ir, is it cu&s;tomary to have female names on pieces of paper of this denomination?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="42" REF="032304_0042_0FF1BC301E9DCC90">
<SPEAKER>Nab&s;on.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, yes, &s;ir, very cu&s;tomary. There are as many ladies who will run into trade&s;men's books, as there are gentlemen; and when one goes to take the ladies, they are a thou&s;and times more &s;lippery to catch than the men.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Abominable&punc;&mdash;Well &s;ir, your pre&s;ent pri&s;oner &s;hall not &s;lip through your hands, if I can prevent it. I &s;corn to defend a worth<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">e&s;s woman, as much as I &s;hould glory in pre&s;erving a good one and I give my&s;elf joy in being the in&s;trument of your executing ju&s;tice&mdash;[<HI>He goes and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ads Mi&s;s</HI> Dorrillon <HI>from the place where &s;he was concealed&mdash;&s;he ca&s;ts down her head</HI>]&mdash;What! do you droop? Do you tremble? You, who at the ball to-night would have danced lightly, though your poor creditor had been peri&s;hing with want! You who never a&s;ked your&s;elf if your extravagance might not &s;end an indu&s;trious father of a family to pri&s;on, can you feel on the pro&s;pect of going thither your&s;elf?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>For what cau&s;e am I the object of your perpe|tual per&s;ecution?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nab&s;on.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lor<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">! Madam, the gentleman means to bail you after all: I can &s;ee it by his looks.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How, ra&s;cal, dare you &s;uppo&s;e, or imagine, or hint, &s;uch a thing? [<HI>going up to him in anger.</HI>]</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That's right, beat him out of the hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No, Madam, he &s;hall not go out of the hou&s;e without taking you along with him. Puni&s;hment may effect in your di&s;po&s;ition what indulgence has no hope of produ|cing.&mdash;There's your pri&s;oner [<HI>handing her over to him</HI>]&mdash;and you may take my word, that &s;he will not be relea&s;ed by me, or by any one: and it will be only adding to a debt &s;he can never pay, to take her to any place previous to a pri&s;on. (<HI>with the emotion of re&s;entment, yet deep &s;orrow.</HI>)</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nab&s;on.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is that true, my lady?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor&punc;</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(after a pau&s;e)</HI> Very true. I have but one friend&mdash;but one relation in the world&mdash;and he is far away.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Weeps.</HI>)</STAGE>
<STAGE>(<HI>Sir</HI> William <HI>wipes his eyes.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nab&s;on.</SPEAKER>
<P>More's the pity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No, &s;ir, no&mdash;no pity at all&mdash;for if fewer <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ine ladies had friends, we &s;hould have fewer examples of profli|gacy. (<HI>She walks to the door, then turns to Sir</HI> William.)</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I forgive you.</P>
<STAGE><HI>(Exit, followed by</HI> Nab&s;on.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sir</HI> William</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(looking after her.)</HI> And perhaps I <HI>could</HI> for|give you. But I mu&s;t not. No, this is ju&s;tice&mdash;this is doing
<PB N="43" REF="032304_0043_0FF1BC3360D4E840">
my duty&mdash;this is &s;trength of mind&mdash;this is fortitude&mdash;forti|tude&mdash;fortitude. <HI>(He walks proudly acro&s;s the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">n, then &s;tops, takes out his handkerchief, throws his head into it, and is going off.)</HI></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lady</HI> Mary&mdash;<HI>a man following at a di&s;tance.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Mandred, Mr. Mandred. <HI>(He turns.)</HI> Sir&mdash;Mr. Mandred&mdash;Sir&mdash;<HI>(in a &s;upp<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">cating tone)</HI> I pre|&s;ume&mdash;I pre&s;ume, &s;ir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What, Madam? what?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I came, &s;ir, to reque&s;t a favour of you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So it &s;hould &s;eem, b<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> that novel deportment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>If you would for once con&s;i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters"> with lenity, frailty incidental to a woman who lives in the gay world&mdash;the</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Madam!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How much &s;he is led away by the tempta|tion of fine cloaths, fine coaches, and fine things.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Come to the bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You are rich, we all know, though you en|deavour to di&s;gui&s;e the truth.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I can't &s;tay to hear you, if you don't proceed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My reque&s;t is&mdash;&s;ave from the dreadful hor|rors of a jail, a woman who has no friend near her&mdash;a woman who may have inadvertent<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">y offended you, but who never&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>it is in vain for you to plead on her account&mdash;&s;he knows my &s;entiments upon her conduct&mdash;&s;he knows the opi|nion I have formed of her&mdash;and you cannot prevail on me to change it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do you &s;uppo&s;e I come to plead fo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> Mi&s;s Dor.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No, I am pleading for my&s;elf. I am un|fortunately involved in &s;imilar circum&s;tances&mdash;I have a &s;imilar debt to the &s;elf-&s;ame trade&s;man, and we are both at pre&s;ent in the &s;elf-&s;ame predicament.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And upon what pretence did you &s;uppo&s;e I would be indulgent to you, more than to her?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e you have always treated me with le&s;s &s;everity; and becau&s;e <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> overheard o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> ju&s;t now &s;ay, you "&s;hould glory in delivering from difficulty a good woman."</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o I &s;hould</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How unlike the world!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;whatever the di&s;contented may plea&s;e to &s;ay, the world is affectionate, is generous, to the good; more e&s;pecially to the good of the female &s;ex; for it is only an ex|ception
<PB N="44" REF="032304_0044_0FF1BC37EB766378">
to a general rule, when a good woman is in pecuniary di&s;tre&s;s.</P>
<STAGE><HI>(Exit Sir</HI> Wm.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lord</HI> Priory, <HI>humming a tune, but with a very &s;erious face: he pulls out his watch with evident marks of anxiety&mdash;coughs&mdash;rubs his forehead&mdash;and gives various other marks of di&s;content and agitation.&mdash;Lady</HI> Mary <HI>ob&s;erves him with attention, then &s;idles up to him.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>By the good humour you appear in, my lord, I venture to mention to you my di&s;tre&s;&s;es. <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> know the virtues of lady Priory makes my fai<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ings con&s;picuous; but then con|&s;ider the different modes to which we have been habituated&mdash;&s;he excluded from temptation&mdash;.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;&s;he &s;huns temptation. Has &s;he not in this very hou&s;e been compelled to make exertions? Has &s;he not detected and expo&s;ed both Mr. Mandred and Mr. Bron.?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Bronzely! Bronzely! How! <HI>(A&s;ide.</HI> A|nother rival?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He has not done with <HI>him</HI> yet, I believe; for to tell the truth, he is now with her at my hou&s;e in Park|&s;treet. He taxed me with being jealous of my wife&mdash;To prove in what contempt I held the accu&s;ation, I left them to|gether, and bid him make love to her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Is that po&s;&s;ible.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I can't &s;ay I would have done &s;o ra&s;h an action, had I been married to &s;ome women&mdash;to you, for in|&s;tance&mdash;but I have not a doubt of Lady Priory's &s;afety: her mind, I know, is &s;ecure, and I have &s;ervants in the hou&s;e to protect her from per&s;ona<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> outrage. The only fear is, le&s;t <HI>he</HI> &s;hould have received one; for 'tis now near two hours <HI>(looking at his watch)</HI> &s;ince I came away, and I have neither &s;een nor heard any thing of either of them!&mdash;But to your lad<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> &s;hip<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">s concerns&punc;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary&punc;</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I am at this in&s;tant, my lord, in the power of an implacable creditor; and without a friend who will give bond for a certain &s;um, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> mu&s;t&mdash;I b<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">u&s;h to name it&mdash;be taken to a pri&s;on</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I am not at all &s;urpri&s;ed at the circum&s;tance, Madam: but it amazes me that you &s;hould apply to me for de|liverance. You have a brother in town; why not &s;end to him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He was my friend the very la&s;t time a di&s;|tre&s;s of this kind befel me. <HI>(Weeps.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A&s;k Mr. Norberry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He was my friend the time before.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="45" REF="032304_0045_0FF1313E73D107A8">
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Bronzely, then.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And Bronzely the time before that.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Oliver.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Oliver! I am glad to &s;ee you, my good fellow. Ha! what have you done with Mr. Bronzely?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oliver.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, my lord, that I can't tell. I can't tell what he has done with him&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How long has he been gone from my hou&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oliver.</SPEAKER>
<P>He is not gone yet as I know of; for none of the &s;ervants let him out.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not gone! and you can't tell where he is!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oliver.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, that we can't: we have looked in every room for him, and can't find him any where.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not find him! <HI>(recollecting him&s;elf)</HI> Ho! ho! I thought how it would be&mdash;I thought he'd have &s;ome trick played him. Where's your lady?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oliver.</SPEAKER>
<P>That I can't tell neither. We have looked in every room, and can't find <HI>her.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oliver.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis as &s;ure as I am alive. I and the butler, two footmen, and all the maids, have been looking in parlours, chambers, and garrets, every crick and corner, and no where can we find either Mr. Bronzely or my lady; but, wherever they are, there's no doubt but they are together. Ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! No doubt at all, Mr. Oliver.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Together! together! and not in my hou&s;e! You tell a fal&s;ehood I'll go my&s;elf and find them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oliver.</SPEAKER>
<P>You mu&s;t look &s;harp, then.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How came you to mi&s;s them?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oliver.</SPEAKER>
<P>I chanced to go into the next room, to &s;ee if there was a proper <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ire to get it well aired; I knew I had taken Mr. Bronzely to my Lady in the inner room, and I had heard them both laughing not a quarter of an hour before; but now, a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">l on a &s;udden, there was neither laughing nor talking, nor any noi&s;e at all&mdash;every thing was &s;o quiet, you might have heard a pin drop.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>anxiou&s;ly.</HI>) Well</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oliver.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o I thought to my&s;elf, thought I, I'll &s;it down here; for my ad<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> will be ringing &s;oon: however, there was no ringing for a whole half hour; and &s;o then I thought I would e'en rap at the door; but nobody called "Come in." So then I went in of my own accord; and there I found&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oliver.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nobody! not a &s;oul to be &s;een!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="46" REF="032304_0046_0FF1BC3AF58A8EE8">
<SPEAKER>Lord, <HI>Priory</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>affecting indifference.</HI>) Oh! &s;he has been playing Bronzely &s;ome trick! She has been hiding him; and in &s;ome mi&s;erable place!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Oliver.</SPEAKER>
<P>But why need &s;he hide her&s;elf along with him?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mr.</HI> Norberry.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr.<HI>Norberry.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My dear friend, my dear lord Priory, let me &s;peak with you alone.&mdash;I come upon bu&s;ine&s;s that&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You look pale! What is your bu&s;ine&s;s? Tell it me at once.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr.<HI>Norberry.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It is of &s;o delicate a nature&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I know my wife is with Mr. Bronzely&mdash;I left them together. I know he is a licentious man; but I know &s;he is an innocent woman.&mdash;Now, what have you to tell me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Norberry.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What I have ju&s;t learnt from one of your &s;ervants. About a quarter of an hour after you left them, they &s;tole &s;oftly out at the back of your hou&s;e, ran to a po&s;t|chai&s;e and four that was in waiting, and drove off together full &s;peed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Gone! eloped! run away from me! left me! left the tendere&s;t, kinde&s;t, mo&s;t indulgent hu&s;band, that ever woman had!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That we can all witne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I was too fond of her&mdash;my affection ruin|ed her&mdash;women are ungrateful&mdash;I did not exert a hu&s;band's authority&mdash;I was not &s;trict enough&mdash;I humoured and &s;poiled her!&mdash;Ble&s;s me! what a thick mi&s;t is come over my eyes!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No, my Lord, it is clearing away.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Lead me to my room. <HI>(He is led off by Mr.</HI> Nor.<HI>exhau&s;ted with grief and anger.)</HI>&mdash;Oliver <HI>looks after Lord</HI> Priory, <HI>then takes out his handkerchief, and follows him off crying.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! Oh, how I enjoy this di&s;tre&s;s&punc; Ha, ha, ha!</P>
<STAGE>The officer who has attended her during the &s;cene, and kept at the farther part of the &s;tage, now comes forward, and bows to her. She &s;tarts on &s;eeing him&mdash;takes out her handkerchief, and goes crying off at the oppo&s;ite &s;ide.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT V.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I. An Apartment at Bronzely's.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Hou&s;ekeeper <HI>and</HI> Footman.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Hous.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dinner enough for twelve, and only two to &s;it
<PB N="47" REF="032304_0047_0FF1BC3E24CC41F0">
down to it! Come home without one preparation&mdash;not a bed aired, or the furniture uncovered.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Foot.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is not the fir&s;t time he has done &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Hous.</SPEAKER>
<P>No; but it's always thus when a woman's in the ca&s;e. Well, I do &s;ay that my own &s;ex are&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Foot.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h! here they are. Run away.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exeunt.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lady</HI> Priory <HI>and Mr.</HI> Bronzely.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Only twelve miles from London?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>No more, be a&s;&s;ured.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And you avow that I did not come hither by the commands of my hu&s;band, but was deceived into that belief by you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Still it was by his commands your &s;ervant intro|duced me to you; and, upon an errand, which I feared to deliver till I arrived at a hou&s;e of my own.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What is the errand?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>To tell you that&mdash;I love you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do you a&s;&s;ert, lord Priory &s;ent you to me for this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>I a&s;&s;ert, that, in triumph at your betraying to him our private appointment, he gave me leave to have a &s;e|cond trial. If, then, you have ever harboured one wi&s;h to revenge, and for&s;ake a churli&s;h ungrateful partner, never re|turn to him more&mdash;but remain with me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And what &s;hall I have gained by the ex|change, when <HI>you</HI> become churli&s;h, when <HI>you</HI> become ungrate|ful? My children's &s;hame! the worlds contempt! and yours! (<HI>Smiling</HI>) Come, come; you are but je&s;ting, Mr. Bronzely! You would not affront my little &s;hare of com|mon &s;en&s;e by making the &s;erious offer of &s;o bad a bargain. Come own the je&s;t, and take me home immediately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is it impo&s;&s;ible for me to excite your tenderne&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Utterly impo&s;&s;ible.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will then rou&s;e your terror.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Even <HI>that</HI> I defy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lady Priory, you are in a lonely hou&s;e of mine, where I <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> ma&s;ter, and all the &s;ervants &s;laves to my will.</P>
<STAGE><HI>(Lady</HI> Priory <HI>calmly takes out her knitting, draws a chair, and &s;its down to knit a pair of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">lockings.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely</SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>a&s;ide.</HI>) This compo&s;ure is wor&s;e than reproach&mdash;a woman who meant to yield would be outrageous.&mdash;<HI>(Goes to &s;peak to her, then turns away.</HI>) By heaven &s;he looks &s;o re&s;|pectable in that employment, I am afraid to in&s;ult her. (<HI>Af|ter a &s;truggle with him&s;elf.</HI>) Ah! don't you fear me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="48" REF="032304_0048_0FF1BC3FAF2B3200">
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;for <HI>your</HI> fears will protect me&mdash;I have no occa&s;ion for my own.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>What have I to fear?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Your fear to lounge no more at routs, at ba<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ls, at operas, in Bond-&s;treet; no more to dance in circles, chat in &s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">de boxes, or roar at taverns: for you have ob&s;erved enough upon the events of life to know&mdash;that an atrocious offence like violence to a woman, never e&s;capes condign puni&s;h|ment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! for once, let your mind be feminine as your per&s;on&mdash;hear the vows&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>he &s;eizes her hand&mdash;&s;he ri&s;es&mdash;he &s;tarts back</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! did not I tell you, you were afraid? 'Tis <HI>you</HI> who are afraid of <HI>me.</HI> (<HI>He looks aba&s;hed.</HI>) Come, you are a&s;hamed, too&mdash;I &s;ee you are, and I pardon you.&mdash;In requital, &s;uffer me to return home immediately. (<HI>He &s;hakes his head.</HI>]&mdash;How! are not you a&s;hamed of your&s;elf?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>I was not this moment&mdash;But now you men|tion it, I think I am.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Repent your fo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ly then, and take me home. <HI>(ha&s;tily).</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can you wi&s;h to go back to the man who has made this trial of your fidelity, and not re&s;ent his conduct?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mo&s;t a&s;&s;uredly I wi&s;h to return. But if you deliver me &s;afe, perfectly &s;afe from farther in&s;ult, it will be impo&s;&s;ible for me not to &s;hew re&s;entment to Lord Priory.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why only in that ca&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e, only in that ca&s;e, you will make an impre&s;&s;ion on m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> heart&mdash;and I will re&s;ent his having expo|&s;ed me to &s;uch a temptation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! I'll take you home directly&mdash;this moment.&mdash;I make an impre&s;&s;ion on your heart. William!&mdash;<HI>(calling)</HI>&mdash;I'll take you home directly. Here John, Thomas, Wil|liam&mdash;<HI>(calling)</HI> But, upon my life, it would be a hard ta&s;k&mdash;I cannot do it&mdash;I am afraid&mdash;I am afraid I cannot&mdash;Be&s;ides, what are we to &s;ay when we go back?&mdash;No matter what, &s;o you will but think kindly of me. (<HI>Enter</HI> Servant.)&mdash;Order the hor&s;es to be put to the chai&s;e; I am going back to London immediately. Quick! quick! Bid the man not be a moment, for fear I &s;hould change my mind.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Serv.</SPEAKER>
<P>The chai&s;e is ready now, Sir; for the po&s;t-boy was going back without unharne&s;&s;ing his hor&s;es.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then tell him he mu&s;t perform his journey in
<PB N="49" REF="032304_0049_0FF1BC41DD20BDC8">
half an hour&mdash;If he is a moment longer, my re&s;olution will &s;top on the road. <HI>(Exit</HI> Ser.) I feel my good de&s;igns &s;teal|ing away a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">read<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&mdash;now they are fl<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">ing rapidly. <HI>(Taking Lady</HI> Priory's <HI>hand)</HI>&mdash;Plea&s;e to look another way&mdash;I &s;hall certainly recant if I &s;ee you. (<HI>Going</HI>)&mdash;And now &s;hould I have the re&s;olution to take you &s;traight to your hu&s;band, you will have made a more contemptible figure of me by this la&s;t trick, than by any one you have played me.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit, leading her off.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>Without</HI>) Tell the po&s;t-boy he need not wait&mdash;I have changed my mind&mdash;I &s;ha<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">n't go to London to-night.</P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE II. A Room in a Pri&s;on.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mi&s;s</HI> Dorril on <HI>and Mr.</HI> Norberry.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You ought to have known it was in vain to &s;end for me. Have not I repeatedly declared, that, till I heard from your father, you &s;hould receive nothing more from me than a bare &s;ub&s;i&s;tence?&mdash;I promi&s;e to allow you thus much, even in this mi&s;erable place: but do not indulge a hope that I can relea&s;e you from it. <HI>(She weeps&mdash;he goes to the door&mdash;then returns.)</HI> I forgot to mention, that Mr. Man|dred goes on board to-morrow for India; and, little as you may think of his &s;en&s;ibility, he &s;eems concerned at the thought of quitting England without ju&s;t bidding you farewel. He came with me hither&mdash;&s;hall I &s;end him up?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! no: for heaven's &s;ake! Deliver me from his a&s;perity, as you would &s;ave me from di&s;traction.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, 'tis for the la&s;t time&mdash;you had better &s;ee him. You may be &s;orry, perhaps, you did not, when he is gone.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No, no; I &s;ha'nt be &s;orry.&mdash;Go and excu&s;e me&mdash;Go, and prevent his coming. I cannot &s;ee him.&mdash;<HI>(Exit Mr.</HI> Norberry)&mdash;This would be aggravation of puni&s;hment, to &s;hut me in a pri&s;on, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> not &s;helter me from the in&s;ults of the world!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Sir</HI> William.&mdash;<HI>(She &s;tarts)</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>&mdash;I know you have de&s;ired not to be troub|led with my vi&s;it; and I come with all humility&mdash;I do not come, be a&s;&s;ured, to reproach you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Unexpected mercy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No; though I have watched your cour&s;e with anger, yet I do not behold its end, with triumph.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It is not to your honour that you think it nece&s;|&s;ary to give this &s;tatement of your mind.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="50" REF="032304_0050_0FF1BC49827B0668">
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>May be&mdash;but I never boa&s;ted of perfection, though I can boa&s;t of grief that I am &s;o far beneath it. I can boa&s;t too, that, though I frequently give offence to others. I could never part with any one for ever (as I now &s;hall with you), without endeavouring to make &s;ome atonement.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You acknowledge, then, your cruelty to me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I acknowledge I have taken upon me to advi&s;e, beyond the liberty allowed by cu&s;tom to one who has no ap|parent intere&s;t or authority.&mdash;But, not to repeat what has pa&s;&s;ed, I come with the approbation of your friend Mr. Nor|berry, to make a propo&s;al to you for the future.</P>
<STAGE>(he draws chairs, and they &s;it.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What propo&s;al?&mdash;What is it? [<HI>eagerly.</HI>]</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Norberry will not give either his money or his word to relea&s;e you&mdash;But as I am rich&mdash;have lo&s;t my only child&mdash;and wi&s;h to do &s;ome good with my fortune, I will in|&s;tantly lay down the money of which you are in want, upon certain conditions.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do I hear right? Is it po&s;&s;ible I can find a friend in <HI>you?</HI>&mdash;a friend to relieve me from the depth of mi&s;ery! Oh Mr. Mandred!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Before you return thanks, hear the conditions on which I make the offer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Any conditions&mdash;What you plea&s;e!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You mu&s;t promi&s;e, never, never to return to your former follies and extr<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">agancies. <HI>(She looks down.)</HI> Do you he&s;itate? Do you refu&s;e?&mdash;Won't you promi&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I would, willingly&mdash;but for one rea&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And what is that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The fear, I &s;hould not keep my word.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You will, if your fear be real.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It <HI>is</HI> real&mdash;It is even &s;o great, that I have no hope.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You refu&s;e my offer then, and di&s;mi&s;s me? (<HI>ri&s;es.</HI>)</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(ri&s;ing al&s;o.)</HI> With much reluctance.&mdash;But I cannot, indeed I cannot make a promi&s;e, unle&s;s I were to feel my heart wholly &s;ubdued; and my mind entirely convinced that <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;hould never break it&mdash;Sir, I am mo&s;t &s;incerely obliged to you for the good which I am &s;ure you de&s;igned me; but do not tempt me with the propo&s;al again&mdash;do not place me in a &s;ituation, that might add to all my other afflictions, the remor&s;e of having deceived you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(after a pau&s;e.)</HI> Well, I will di&s;pen&s;e with
<PB N="51" REF="032304_0051_0FF1BC4B096A37A0">
this condition&mdash;but there is another I mu&s;t &s;ub&s;titute in its &s;tead.&mdash;Re&s;olve to pa&s;s the remainder of your life, &s;ome few en&s;uing years at lea&s;t, in the country. <HI>(She &s;tarts.)</HI> Do you &s;tart at that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I do not love the country. I am always mi|&s;erable while I am from London. Be&s;ides, there are no fol|lies or extravagancies in the country.&mdash;Dear Sir, this is giv|ing me up the fir&s;t condition, and then forcing me to keep it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There, Madam, <HI>(taking out his pocket-book)</HI> I &s;corn to hold out hopes, and then de&s;troy them. There is a thou&s;and pounds free of all conditions <HI>(&s;he takes it)</HI>&mdash;extri|cate your&s;elf from this &s;ituation, and be your own mi&s;tre&s;s to return to it when you plea&s;e.</P>
<STAGE>(Going.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, my benefactor, bid me farewell at part|ing&mdash;do not leave me in anger.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How! will you dictate terms to me, while you reject a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">l mine?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then only &s;uffer me to expre&s;s my gratitude&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I will not hear you.</P>
<STAGE>(going.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then hear me on another &s;ubject: a &s;ubject of much importance&mdash;indeed it is.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You are going to India immediately&mdash;It is po&s;&s;ible that there, or at &s;ome place you will &s;top at on your way, you may meet with my father.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You have heard that I have expected him home for &s;ome time pa&s;t, and that I &s;till live in hopes.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well!&mdash;<HI>(anxiou&s;ly)</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>If you &s;hould &s;ee him, and &s;hould be in his company&mdash;don't mention <HI>me.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not mention <HI>you?</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>At lea&s;t, not my indi&s;cretions&mdash;Oh! I &s;hould die, if I thought <HI>he</HI> would ever know of them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do you think he would not di&s;cover them him|&s;elf, &s;hould he ever &s;ee you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But he would not di&s;cover them all at once&mdash;I &s;hould be on my guard when he fir&s;t came&mdash;My ill habits would &s;teal on him progre&s;&s;ively, and not be half &s;o &s;hocking, as if you were to vociferate them all in a breath.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To put you out of apprehen&s;ion at once&mdash;your father is not coming home&mdash;nor will he ever return to his own country.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="52" REF="032304_0052_0FF1BC4C93DBB998">
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(&s;tarting.)</STAGE>
<P>You &s;eem to &s;peak from certain knowledge&mdash;Oh! heavens! is he not living?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, living&mdash;but under &s;evere affliction&mdash;fortune has changed, and all his hopes are bla&s;ted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>"Fortune has changed!"&mdash;In povert<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">?&mdash;my father in poverty?&mdash;<HI>(wee<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ing)</HI>&mdash;Oh&punc; Sir&punc; excu&s;e, what may perhaps appear an ill comp<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">iment to your bounty; but to me, the greate&s;t reverence I can pay to it.&mdash;You are going to that part of the world where he is; take this precious gift back, &s;earch out my father and let <HI>him</HI> be the object of your beneficence.&mdash;[<HI>Forces it into his hand.</HI>]&mdash;I &s;hall be happy in this pri&s;on, indeed <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;hall, &s;o <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> can but give a momentary relief to my dear, dear father.&mdash;[<HI>Sir</HI> William <HI>takes out his handker|chief</HI>]&mdash;You weep:&mdash;This pre&s;ent, perhaps, would be but poor alleviation of his &s;ufferings&mdash;perhaps he is in &s;ickne&s;s; or a pri&s;oner: Oh! if he is relea&s;e me in&s;tantly, and take me with you to the place of his confinement.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What! quit the joys of London?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>On &s;uch an errand, I would quit them all without a &s;igh&mdash;And here I make a &s;olemn promi&s;e to you&mdash;<HI>(kneeling.)</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm&punc;</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hold, you may wi&s;h to break it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Never&mdash;exact what vow you will on <HI>this</HI> oc|ca&s;ion, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> will make, and keep it.&mdash;[<HI>Enter Mr.</HI> Norberry.&mdash;<HI>She ri&s;es.</HI>]&mdash;Oh! Mr Norberry, he has been telling me &s;uch things of my father&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Has he? Then kneel again&mdash;call <HI>him</HI> by that name&mdash;and implore him not to di&s;own <HI>you</HI> for his child.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Good heaven!&mdash;I dare not&mdash;I dare not do as you require. [<HI>She faints on</HI> Norberry.]</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(going to her)</HI> My daughter!&mdash;My child!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>At tho&s;e names &s;he revives.&mdash;(<HI>She rai&s;es her <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, but expre&s;&s;es great agitation.</HI>)&mdash;Come, let us quit this wretched place&mdash;&s;he will be better then. My carriage is at the door. You will follow us.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exeunt, leading off Mi&s;s</HI> Dorrillon.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Follow you!&mdash;Yes&mdash;and I perceive that, in &s;pite of philo&s;ophy, ju&s;tice, or re&s;olution, I could follow you all the world over.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE III. Another Room in the Pri&s;on.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Lady</HI> Mary <HI>di&s;covered &s;itting in a dejected po&s;ture, at a mi|&s;erable table.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Provoking<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> not an an&s;wer to one of my
<PB N="53" REF="032304_0053_0FF1BC530DD67EE8">
pathetic letters!&mdash;no<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> a creature to come and condole with me!&mdash;Oh that <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> could but regain my liberty before my di&s;|grace is announced in the public prints&mdash;I could then boldly contradict every paragraph that a&s;&s;erted it&mdash;by <Q>We have authority to &s;ay, no &s;uch event ever took p<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ace.</Q></P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter a Man belonging to the pri&s;on.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Man.</SPEAKER>
<P>One Sir George Eve<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">yn is here, Madam; he will not name your name, becau&s;e it &s;ha'n't be made public; but he de&s;ires you will permit him to come and &s;peak a few words to you, provided <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ou are the young lady from Gro&s;venor-&s;treet, with whom he has the plea&s;ure of being acquainted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, I am the young lady from Gro&s;|venor-&s;treet&mdash;my compliments to Sir George, I am that lady; intimately acquainted with him; and entreat he will wa<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">k up. (<HI>Exit the Man.</HI>) This is a mo&s;t fortunate incident in my tragedy! Sir George no doubt takes me for Mi&s;s Dorrillon; yet I am &s;ure he is too much the man of gallantry and good breeding to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">eave me in this p<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ace, although he vi&s;its me by mi&s;take.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Sir</HI> George Evelyn <HI>(&s;peaking as he enters)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, you are free&mdash;the doors of the pri|&s;on are open&mdash;my word is pa&s;&s;ed for the&mdash;[<HI>He &s;tops</HI>&mdash;<HI>looks around</HI>&mdash;<HI>expre&s;&s;es &s;urpri&s;e and confu&s;ion.</HI>]</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(curt&s;ying very low)</HI> Sir George, I am under the mo&s;t infinite obligation!&mdash;Words are too poor to convey the &s;en&s;e I have of this act of friend&s;hip&mdash;but <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> tru&s;t my gratitude will for ever&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>confu&s;e<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">.</HI>) Madam&mdash;really&mdash;I ought to apo|logi&s;e for the libert<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> I have taken.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No liberty at all, Sir George&mdash;at lea&s;t no apology is nece&s;&s;ary&mdash;I in&s;i&s;t on hearing no excu&s;es. A vir|tuous action requires no preface, no prologue, no ceremony&mdash;and &s;urely, if one action be more noble and generous than another, it mu&s;t be that one, where an act of benevolence is conferred, and the object, an object of tota<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> indifference to the libera<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> benefactor&mdash;Generous man, good evening&mdash;Call me a coach.</P>
<STAGE>[going]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Stay, Madam&mdash;I beg leave to &s;ay&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>&mdash;Not a word&mdash;I won't hear a word&mdash;my thanks &s;hall drown whatever you have to &s;ay.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter the former</HI> Man.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, Sir, did not you tell me, you had a very young lady under your care?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="54" REF="032304_0054_0FF1BC561C277D30">
<SPEAKER>Man.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir, &s;o I had&mdash;but &s;he, it &s;eems, has ju&s;t been relea&s;ed, and is gone away with the gentleman who paid the debt</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do you mean Mi&s;s Dorrillon?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Man.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mean the other lady from Gro&s;venor-&s;treet.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Who can have relea&s;ed her?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Some friend of <HI>mine,</HI> I dare &s;ay, by mi&s;|take&mdash;Well, if it is &s;o, &s;he is extremely welcome to the good fortune which was de&s;igned for <HI>me.</HI> For my part, I could not &s;ubmit to an obligation from every one&mdash;&s;carcely from any one&mdash;and from no one with &s;o little regret as I &s;ubmit to it from Sir George Evelyn.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit, curt&s;ying to Sir</HI> George.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Di&s;traction! the fir&s;t di&s;appointment is nothing to this &s;econd! to the reflection that Mi&s;s Dorrillon has been &s;et at liberty by any man on earth except my&s;elf.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE IV. An Apartment at Mr. Norberry's.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lord</HI> Priory</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What a &s;ituation is mine! I cannot bear &s;o|litude, and am a&s;hamed to &s;ee company! I cannot bear to think on the ungrateful woman, and yet I can think of nothing el&s;e! <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">t was her conduct which I imagined had alone charmed me; but I perceive her power over my heart, though that conduct is changed!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mr.</HI> Norberry, <HI>Sir</HI> William, <HI>and Mi&s;s</HI> Dorrillon.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Nor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Lord Priory, exert <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">our &s;pirits to re|ceive and congratulate a friend of mine. Sir William Dor|rillon <HI>(pre&s;enting him)</HI> father to this young woman, who&s;e failings he has endeavoured to correct under the borrowed name of Mandred.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And with that fictitious name, I hope to di&s;bur|then my&s;elf of the imputation of having ever offered an af|front to my lord Priory. <HI>(He takes Lord</HI> Priory <HI>a&s;ide, and they talk together.)</HI></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Sir</HI> George Evelyn.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Is it po&s;&s;ible what <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> have heard is true? was it Mr. Mandred who has re&s;tored Mi&s;s Dorrillon to the pro|tection of Mr. Norberry?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>coming forward.</HI>) No, Sir George, I have now taken her under my own protection.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>By what tit<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">e, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A very tender one&mdash;don't be alarmed&mdash;I am her father.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="55" REF="032304_0055_0FF1BC592B54B278">
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Wm. Dorrillon? (<HI>They talk apart.</HI>)</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lady</HI> Mary.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Has there been any intelligence of my Lady Priory yet? (<HI>&s;ees Mi&s;s</HI> Dorrillon) My dear Dorrillon, a lover of yours has done the civile&s;t thing by me!&mdash;As I live, here he is. How do you do, Sir George? I &s;uppo&s;e you have all heard the news of Bronzely running away with&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h!&mdash;Lord Priory is here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, he knows it&mdash;and it is not improper to remind him of it&mdash;it will teach him humility.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory&punc;</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I <HI>am</HI> humble, Lady Mary, and own I have had a better opinion of your &s;ex than I ought to have had.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You mean, of your management of us; of your in&s;tructions, re&s;trictions, and corrections.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Servant.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Servant.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lady Priory and Mr. Bronzely.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What of them?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Serv.</SPEAKER>
<P>They are here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;aid &s;he'd pre&s;erve her fidelity! Did not I always &s;ay &s;o? Have I wavered once? Did I not always tell you all that &s;he was only making game of Bronzely? Did I not tell you all &s;o?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Bronzely <HI>and Lady</HI> Priory.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, indeed, my Lord, you &s;aid truly; for I return the arrante&s;t blockhead&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I always &s;aid you would! But how is it? Where have you been? What occa&s;ion for a po&s;t-chai&s;e? In&s;tantly explain, or I &s;hall forfeit that dignity of a hu&s;band, to which, in tho&s;e degenerate times, I have almo&s;t an exclu|&s;ive right.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>To rei<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;tate you<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> my Lord, in tho&s;e honours, I accompany Lady Priory; and beg public pardon for the opinion I once publicly profe&s;&s;ed, of your want of influence over her affections.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do you hear? Do you all hear? Lady Mary, do <HI>you</HI> hear?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Bronz<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ly.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Taking advantage of your permi&s;&s;ion to call on her, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;tratagem I induced her to quit your hou&s;e, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">&s;t re|&s;traint might there act as my enemy. But your authority, your prerogative your honour attached to her under my roof. She has held tho&s;e rights &s;acred, and compelled even <HI>me</HI> to revere them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="56" REF="032304_0056_0FF1BC5AC6D8E248">
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do you all hear? I was &s;ure it would turn out &s;o!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>This is the fir&s;t time I ever knew the gal|lant's word taken for a woman's honour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I will take her own word&mdash;the tongue which for eleven years has never in the &s;lighte&s;t in&s;tance de|ceived me, I wil<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> believe upon all occa&s;ions. My dear wife, boldly pronounce before this company that you return to me with the &s;ame affection and re&s;pect, and the &s;elf-&s;ame con|tempt for this man&mdash;<HI>(to</HI> Bron.<HI>)</HI>&mdash;you ever had.</P>
<STAGE>[a &s;hort pau&s;e.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>She makes no an&s;wer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h! Hu&s;h! She is going to &s;peak.&mdash;<HI>(Another pau&s;e)</HI>&mdash;Why, why don't you &s;peak?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e I am at a lo&s;s what to &s;ay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hear, hear, hear&mdash;do you all hear?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Can you be at a lo&s;s to declare you hate Mr. Bronzely?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I do <HI>not</HI> hate him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I was &s;ure it would turn out &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Can you be at a lo&s;s to &s;ay you love me?</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>She appears embarra&s;&s;ed.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>She <HI>is</HI> at a lo&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How! Don't you fear me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>She &s;peaks pla<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ly to that que&s;tion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You know I love truth&mdash;&s;peak plainly to all their curio&s;ity requires.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Since you command it then, my Lord&mdash;I confe&s;s that Mr. Bronzeley's conduct towards me has cau&s;ed a kind of &s;entiment in my heart&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hah! what?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You mu&s;t believe her&mdash;"&s;he has told you truth for eleven years."</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A &s;en&s;ation which&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Stop&mdash;any truth but this I could have borne&mdash;Reflect on what you are &s;aying&mdash;Con&s;ider what you are do|ing&mdash;Are the&s;e your primitive manners?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hould have continued tho&s;e manners, had I known none but primitive men. But to pre&s;erve ancient au&s;terity, while, by my hu&s;band's con&s;ent. I am a&s;&s;ailed by modern gallantry, would be the ta&s;k of a &s;to<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">, and not of hi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> female &s;lave.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="57" REF="032304_0057_0FF1BC5DD1ECE5D0">
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do you hear? Do you all hear? My Lord, do <HI>you</HI> hear?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I do&mdash;I do&mdash;and though the &s;ound di&s;tracts me, I cannot doubt her word.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It gives me exce&s;&s;ive joy to hear you &s;ay &s;o, becau&s;e you will not then doubt me when I add&mdash;that gratitude, for his re&s;toring me &s;o &s;oon to you is the only &s;entiment he has in&s;pired.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then my management of a wife is right after all!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Norberry.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Bronzely, as your pre&s;ent behaviour has in great mea&s;ure atoned for your former actions, I will introduce to your acquaintance my friend Sir William Dor|rillon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mandred, Sir William Dorrillon!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And con&s;idering, Sir, that upon one or two occa&s;ions I have been honoured with your confidence&mdash;you will not be &s;urpri&s;ed, if the fir&s;t command I lay upon my daughter, is&mdash;to take refuge from your pur&s;uits, in the protec|tion of Sir George Evelyn.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And may I hope, Maria?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;I will in&s;tantly put an end to all your hopes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir&punc; <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Wm.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>By rai&s;ing you to the &s;ummit of your wi&s;hes. Alarmed at my &s;everity, &s;he has owned her readine&s;s to be|come the &s;ubject of a milder government.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>She &s;hall never repin<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> at the election &s;he has made.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But, Sir George, if you are a prudent man, you will fix your eyes on my little dome&s;tic &s;tate, and guard again&s;t a rebellion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Priory.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not the rigour of its laws has ever induced me to wi&s;h them aboli&s;hed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bronzely</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(<HI>to Lady</HI> Priory.)</STAGE>
<P>Dear Lady, you have made me think with reverence on the matrimonial compact: and I demand of you, Lady Mary&mdash;if, in con&s;equence of former overtures, I &s;hould e&s;tabli&s;h a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">egal authority over you, and become your chief magi&s;trate&mdash;would you &s;ubmit to the &s;ame controul to which Lady Priory &s;ubmits?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>Mary.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Any controul, rather than have no chief magi&s;trate at all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="58" REF="032304_0058_0FF1BC6267216138">
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>George</HI></SPEAKER>
<STAGE>[<HI>to Mi&s;s</HI> Dor.]</STAGE>
<P>And what do you &s;ay to this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Simply one &s;entence&mdash;A maid of the pre&s;ent day &s;hall become a wife like tho&s;e&mdash;of former times.</P>
<STAGE>The &s;cene clo&s;es&mdash;She comes forward.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="epilogue">
<HEAD>ADDRESS, WRITTEN BY MR. TAYLOR; SPOKEN BY MISS WALLIS.</HEAD>
<LG>
<L><HI>WELL, female critics, what's the &s;entence, &s;ay&mdash;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Can you with kindne&s;s treat this &s;aucy play,</HI></L>
<L><HI>That gives to ancient dames the wreath of prai&s;e</HI></L>
<L><HI>And boldly cen&s;ures tho&s;e of modern days?</HI></L>
<L><HI>Bring us good hu&s;bands fir&s;t, and, on my life,</HI></L>
<L><HI>For every one we'll &s;hew as good a wife.</HI></L>
<L><HI>Whate'er the errors in the nuptial &s;tate,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Man &s;ets th' example to his pa&s;&s;ive mate:</HI></L>
<L><HI>While all the virtues the proud &s;ex can claim</HI></L>
<L><HI>From female influence<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> caught the gen'rous flame.</HI></L>
<L><HI>Nay, though our gallant rulers of the main</HI></L>
<L><HI>With force re&s;i&s;tle&s;s <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">rush the pride of Spain;</HI></L>
<L><HI>'Tis Woman triumphs&mdash;that in&s;piring charm</HI></L>
<L><HI>With tenfold vigour nerves the hero's arm:</HI></L>
<L><HI>For King and Country though they nobly bleed,</HI></L>
<L><HI>The &s;mile of Beauty is their deare&s;t m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ed.</HI></L>
<L><HI>And valiant tars &s;hould &s;till be Beauty's care</HI></L>
<L><HI>Since 'its "the brave alone de&s;erve the fair."</HI></L>
</LG>
